# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: antikythera-wreck
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] Around 5,000 BC, peoples descending from migrant Greek Neolithic populations reached the northern European plain in modern-day France and Germany; they reached Britain some 1000 years later.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] Once in the Balkans, the Aegean EEFs appear to have divided into two wings: one which expanded further north into Europe along the Danube (Linear Pottery culture), and another which headed west along the Mediterranean (Cardial Ware) into the Iberian Peninsula.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] Descendants of this latter group eventually migrated into Britain.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] Previously, these areas were populated by Western Hunter-Gatherer represented by the Cheddar Man.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] The Chalcolithic (Copper Age) began in Europe around 5500 BC.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] Chalcolithic Europeans began to erect megaliths in this period.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] Commerce was practiced to some extent in very early times, as is shown by the distribution of Melian obsidian over all the Aegean area.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] Cretan vessels appeared to be exported to Melos, Egypt, and the Greek mainland.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] In particular, Melian vases, eventually, found their way to Crete.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] After 1600 BC, there was commerce with Egypt, and Aegean goods found their way to all coasts of the Mediterranean.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] No traces of currency have come to light, excluding certain axeheads.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] These axeheads were too small for practical use.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] Standard weights have been found, as well as representations of ingots.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] The Aegean written documents have not yet been proven (by being found outside the area) to be epistolary (letter writing) correspondence with other countries.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] Representations of ships are not common, but several have been observed on Aegean gems, gem-sealings, frying pans, and vases.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] These vases feature ships of low free-board, with masts and oars.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] Familiarity with the sea is proved by the free use of marine motifs in decoration.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] The most detailed illustrations are to be found on the 'ship fresco' at Akrotiri on the island of Thera (Santorini) preserved by the ash fall from the volcanic eruption which destroyed the town there.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] Discoveries, later in the 20th century, of sunken trading vessels such as those at Uluburun and Cape Gelidonya off the south coast of Turkey have brought forth an enormous amount of new information about that culture.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] For details of monumental evidence the articles on Crete, Mycenae, Tiryns, Troad, Cyprus, etc., must be consulted.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] The most representative site explored up to now is Knossos (see Crete) which has yielded not only the most various but the most continuous evidence from the Neolithic age to the twilight of classical civilization.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] Next in importance come Hissarlik, Mycenae, Phaestus, Hagia Triada, Tiryns, Phylakope, Palaikastro and Gournia.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] Mycenae and Tiryns are the two principal sites on which evidence of a prehistoric civilization was remarked long ago by the ancient Greeks.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] The curtain-wall and towers of the Mycenaean citadel, its gate with heraldic lions, and the great "Treasury of Atreus" had borne silent witness for ages before Heinrich Schliemann's time.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] However, they were regarded as a crude precursor of later Greek culture.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] It was not until Schliemann's excavations that Mycenaean culture attracted serious scholarly attention.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] There had been, however, a good deal of other evidence available before 1876, which, had it been collated and seriously studied, might have discounted the sensation that the discovery of the citadel graves eventually made.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] For instance, scholars had noted that tributaries appearing in Egyptian art resembled modern Greeks, but were unable to definitely recognize them as such.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] Nor did the Aegean objects which were lying obscurely in museums in 1870, or thereabouts, provide a sufficient test of the real basis underlying the Hellenic myths of the Argolid, the Troad and Crete, to cause these to be taken seriously.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] Aegean vases have been exhibited both at Sèvres and Neuchatel since about 1840, the provenance (i.e. source or origin) being in the one case Phylakope in Melos, in the other Cephalonia.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] Newton demonstrated these to be no strayed Phoenician products.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] In 1866 primitive structures were discovered on the island of Therasia by quarrymen extracting pozzolana, a siliceous volcanic ash, for the Suez Canal works.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] When this discovery was followed up in 1870, on the neighbouring Santorini (Thera), by representatives of the French School at Athens, much pottery of a class now known immediately to precede the typical late Aegean ware, and many stone and metal objects, were found.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] These were dated by the geologist Ferdinand A.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] Fouqué, somewhat arbitrarily, to 2000 BC, by consideration of the superincumbent eruptive stratum.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] Nor was a connection immediately detected between them and the objects found four years later in a tomb at Menidi in Attica and a rock-cut "bee-hive" grave near the Argive Heraeum.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] Even Schliemann's initial excavations at Hissarlik in the Troad did not excite surprise.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] However, the "Burnt City" now known as Troy II, revealed in 1873, with its fortifications and vases, and a hoard of gold, silver, and bronze objects, which the discoverer connected with it, began to arouse curiosity both among scholars and the general public.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] With Schliemann's excavations at Mycenae, interest in prehistoric Greece exploded.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] It was recognized that the character of both the fabric and the decoration of the Mycenaean objects was not that of any previously known style.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] A wide range in space was proved by the identification of the Inselsteine and the Ialysus vases with the new style, and a wide range in time by collation of the earlier Theraean and Hissarlik discoveries.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] Many scholars were struck by potential resemblances between objects described by Homer and Mycenaean artifacts.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] Schliemann resumed excavations at Hissarlik in 1878, and greatly increased our knowledge of the lower strata, but did not recognize the Aegean remains in his "Lydian" city now known as Late Bronze Age Troy.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] These were not to be fully revealed until Dr.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] Wilhelm Dorpfeld, who had become Schliemann's assistant in 1879, resumed the work at Hissarlik in 1892 after Schliemann's death.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] But by laying bare in 1884 the upper stratum of remains on the rock of Tiryns, Schliemann made a contribution to our knowledge of prehistoric domestic life which was amplified two years later by Christos Tsountas's discovery of the palace at Mycenae.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] Schliemann's work at Tiryns was not resumed till 1905, when it was proved, as had long been suspected, that an earlier palace underlies the one he had exposed.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] From 1886 dates the finding of Mycenaean sepulchres outside the Argolid, from which, and from the continuation of Tsountas's exploration of the buildings and lesser graves at Mycenae, a large treasure, independent of Schliemann's princely gift, has been gathered into the National Museum at Athens.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] In that year tholos-tombs, most already pillaged but retaining some of their furniture, were excavated at Arkina and Eleusis in Attica, at Dimini near Volos in Thessaly, at Kampos on the west of Mount Taygetus, and at Maskarata in Cephalonia.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] During the Acropolis excavations in Athens, which terminated in 1888, many potsherds of the Mycenaean style were found; but Olympia had yielded either none, or such as had not been recognized before being thrown away, and the temple site at Delphi produced nothing distinctively Aegean (in dating).
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] The American explorations of the Argive Heraeum, concluded in 1895, also failed to prove that site to have been important in the prehistoric time, though, as was to be expected from its neighbourhood to Mycenae itself, there were traces of occupation in the later Aegean periods.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] Prehistoric research had now begun to extend beyond the Greek mainland.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] Certain central Aegean islands, Antiparos, Ios, Amorgos, Syros and Siphnos, were all found to be singularly rich in evidence of the Middle-Aegean period.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] The series of Syran-built graves, containing crouching corpses, is the best and most representative that is known in the Aegean.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] Melos, long marked as a source of early objects but not systematically excavated until taken in hand by the British School at Athens in 1896, yielded at Phylakope remains of all the Aegean periods, except the Neolithic.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] A map of Cyprus in the later Bronze Age (such as is given by J.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] Richter in Catalogue of the Cyprus Museum) shows more than 25 settlements in and about the Mesaorea district alone, of which one, that at Enkomi, near the site of Salamis, has yielded the richest Aegean treasure in precious metal found outside Mycenae.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] In Egypt in 1887, Flinders Petrie found painted sherds of Cretan style at Kahun in the Fayum, and farther up the Nile, at Tell el-Amarna, chanced on bits of no fewer than 800 Aegean vases in 1889.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] There have now been recognized in the collections at Cairo, Florence, London, Paris and Bologna several Egyptian imitations of the Aegean style which can be set off against the many debts which the centres of Aegean culture owed to Egypt.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] Two Aegean vases were found at Sidon in 1885, and many fragments of Aegean and especially Cypriot pottery have been found during recent excavations of sites in Philistia by the Palestine Fund.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] Orsi excavated the Sicel cemetery near Lentini in 1877, has proved a mine of early remains, among which appear in regular succession Aegean fabrics and motives of decoration from the period of the second stratum at Hissarlik.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] Sardinia has Aegean sites, for example, at Abini near Teti; and Spain has yielded objects recognized as Aegean from tombs near Cádiz and from Saragossa.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] One land, however, has eclipsed all others in the Aegean by the wealth of its remains of all the prehistoric ages— Crete; and so much so that, for the present, we must regard it as the fountainhead of Aegean civilization, and probably for long its political and social centre.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] The island first attracted the notice of archaeologists by the remarkable archaic Greek bronzes found in a cave on Mount Ida in 1885, as well as by epigraphic monuments such as the famous law of Gortyna (also called Gortyn).
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] But the first undoubted Aegean remains reported from it were a few objects extracted from Cnossus by Minos Kalokhairinos of Candia in 1878.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] These were followed by certain discoveries made in the S. plain Messara by F.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] Unsuccessful attempts at Cnossus were made by both W.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] Evans, coming on the scene in 1893, travelled in succeeding years about the island picking up trifles of unconsidered evidence, which gradually convinced him that greater things would eventually be found.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] He obtained enough to enable him to forecast the discovery of written characters, till then not suspected in Aegean civilization.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] The revolution of 1897–1898 opened the door to wider knowledge, and much exploration has ensued, for which see Crete.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] Thus the "Aegean Area" has now come to mean the Archipelago with Crete and Cyprus, the Hellenic peninsula with the Ionian islands, and Western Anatolia.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] Evidence is still wanting for the Macedonian and Thracian coasts.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] Offshoots are found in the western Mediterranean area, in Sicily, Italy, Sardinia and Spain, and in the eastern Mediterranean area in Syria and Egypt.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] Regarding the Cyrenaica, we are still insufficiently informed.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] The final collapse of the Mycenaean civilisation appears to have occurred about 1200 BC.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-civilization] Iron took the place of bronze, cremation took the place of burial of the dead, and writing was lost.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The **Aegean Sea** is an elongated embayment of the Mediterranean Sea between Europe and Asia.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] It is located between the Balkans and Anatolia, and covers an area of some 215,000 km2 (83,000 sq mi).
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] In the north, the Aegean is connected to the Marmara Sea, which in turn connects to the Black Sea, by the straits of the Dardanelles and the Bosphorus, respectively.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The Aegean Islands are located within the sea and some bound it on its southern periphery, including Crete and Rhodes.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The sea reaches a maximum depth of 2,639 m (8,658 ft) to the west of Karpathos.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The Thracian Sea and the Sea of Crete are main subdivisions of the Aegean Sea.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The Aegean Islands can be divided into several island groups, including the Dodecanese, the Cyclades, the Sporades, the Saronic islands and the North Aegean Islands, as well as Crete and its surrounding islands.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The Dodecanese, located to the southeast, includes the islands of Rhodes, Kos, and Patmos; the islands of Delos and Naxos are within the Cyclades to the south of the sea.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] Lesbos is part of the North Aegean Islands.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] Euboea, the second-largest island in Greece, is located in the Aegean, despite being administered as part of Central Greece.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] Nine out of twelve of the Administrative regions of Greece border the sea, along with the Turkish provinces of Edirne, Çanakkale, Balıkesir, İzmir, Aydın and Muğla to the east of the sea.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] Various Turkish islands in the sea are Imbros, Tenedos, Cunda Island, and the Foça Islands.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The Aegean Sea has been historically important, especially regarding the civilization of Ancient Greece, which inhabited the area around the coast of the Aegean and the Aegean islands.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The Aegean islands facilitated contact between the people of the area and between Europe and Asia.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] Along with the Greeks, Thracians lived along the northern coasts.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The Romans conquered the area under the Roman Empire, and later the Byzantine Empire held it against advances by the First Bulgarian Empire.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The Fourth Crusade weakened Byzantine control of the area, and it was eventually conquered by the Ottoman Empire, with the exception of Crete, which was a Venetian colony until 1669.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The Greek War of Independence allowed a Greek state on the coast of the Aegean from 1829 onwards.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The Ottoman Empire held a presence over the sea for over 500 years until it was replaced by modern Turkey.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The rocks making up the floor of the Aegean are mainly limestone, though often greatly altered by volcanic activity that has convulsed the region in relatively recent geologic times.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] Of particular interest are the richly colored sediments in the region of the islands of Santorini and Milos, in the south Aegean.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] Notable cities on the Aegean coastline include Athens, Thessaloniki, Heraklion, Volos, Alexandroupolis and Kavala in Greece, and İzmir and Bodrum in Turkey.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] Several issues concerning sovereignty within the Aegean Sea are disputed between Greece and Turkey.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The Aegean dispute has had a large effect on Greece-Turkey relations since the 1970s.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] Issues include the delimitation of territorial waters, national airspace, exclusive economic zones, and flight information regions.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] Ancient Greek authors also called it the "Greek Sea".
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The sea was known in Latin as *Mare Aegaeum* while under the control of the Roman Empire.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] Pliny the Elder write that the Romans used the terms "Macedonian" for the northern part near Macedonia and Thrace provinces, and "Grecian" for the part near Greece itself.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] In medieval Latin, the Aegean Sea was known as *Egeopelagus*, a form attested as late as 1419 in Venetian state papers (Ducatus Egeopelagi) and derived from the Greek αἰγαιοπέλαγος / αἰγαῖον πέλαγος.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The term *Arcipelago* also appears, for instance in a treaty on 30 June 1268 between the Venetians and the emperor Michael Palaeologus.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] This term subsequently gave rise to *Archipelago* (Greek: αρχιπέλαγος), which in many European languages originally referred specifically to the Aegean Sea.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The terms *Greek Archipelago* or *Grecian Archipelago* were also used.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] Later, as archipelago came to be used increasingly as a generic term for island-studded seas, the terms Greek Archipelago or Grecian Archipelago continued to be used alongside the ancient name, Aegean Sea.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] In some South Slavic languages, the Aegean is called *White Sea* (Bulgarian: Бяло море, romanized: *Byalo more*; Macedonian: Бело море, romanized: *Belo more*; Serbian: *Belo more* / Бело море).
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The Turkish name for the sea is *Ege Denizi*, which is derived from the Greek name, and *Adalar Denizi* meaning "Sea of Islands".
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] In the past, Turks also referred to it as the "White Sea", to differentiate it from the Black Sea.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The Aegean Sea is an elongated embayment of the Mediterranean Sea and covers about 214,000 square kilometres (83,000 sq mi) in area, measuring about 670 kilometres (420 mi) longitudinally and 390 kilometres (240 mi) latitudinal.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The sea's maximum depth is 2,639 metres (8,658 ft), located at a point west of Karpathos.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The Aegean Islands are found within its waters, with the following islands delimiting the sea on the south, generally from west to east: Kythera, Antikythera, Crete, Kasos, Karpathos and Rhodes.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The Anatolian peninsula marks the eastern boundary of the sea, while the Greek mainland marks the west.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] Several seas are contained within the Aegean Sea; the Thracian Sea is a section of the Aegean located to the north, the Icarian Sea to the east, the Myrtoan Sea to the west, while the Sea of Crete is the southern section.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The Greek regions that border the sea, in alphabetical order, are Attica, Central Greece, Central Macedonia, Crete, Eastern Macedonia and Thrace, North Aegean, Peloponnese, South Aegean, and Thessaly.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The traditional Greek region of Macedonia also borders the sea, to the north.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] Many of the Aegean islands or island chains, are geographical extensions of the mountains on the mainland.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] One chain extends across the sea to Chios, another extends across Euboea to Samos, and a third extends across the Peloponnese and Crete to Rhodes, dividing the Aegean from the Mediterranean.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The Aegean Sea is connected to the Sea of Marmara by the Dardanelles, also known from Classical Antiquity as the Hellespont.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The Dardanelles are located to the northeast of the sea.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] It ultimately connects with the Black Sea through the Bosporus strait, upon which lies the city of Istanbul.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The Dardanelles and the Bosporus are known as the Turkish Straits.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] Aegean surface water circulates in a counterclockwise gyre, with hypersaline Mediterranean water moving northward along the west coast of Turkey, before being displaced by less dense Black Sea outflow.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The dense Mediterranean water sinks below the Black Sea inflow to a depth of 23–30 metres (75–98 ft), then flows through the Dardanelles Strait and into the Sea of Marmara at velocities of 5–15 cm/s (2–6 in/s).
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The Black Sea outflow moves westward along the northern Aegean Sea, then flows southwards along the east coast of Greece.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The physical oceanography of the Aegean Sea is controlled mainly by the regional climate, the fresh water discharge from major rivers draining southeastern Europe, and the seasonal variations in the Black Sea surface water outflow through the Dardanelles Strait.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The climate of the Aegean Sea largely reflects the climate of Greece and Western Turkey, which is to say, predominantly Mediterranean.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] According to the Köppen climate classification, most of the Aegean is classified as Hot-summer Mediterranean (*Csa*), with hotter and drier summers along with milder and wetter winters.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] However, high temperatures during summers are generally not quite as high as those in arid or semiarid climates due to the presence of a large body of water.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] This is most predominant in the west and east coasts of the Aegean, and within the Aegean islands.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] In the north of the Aegean Sea, the climate is instead classified as Cold semi-arid *(BSk)*, which feature cooler summers than Hot-summer Mediterranean climates.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The Etesian winds are a dominant weather influence in the Aegean Basin.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] Numerous Greek and Turkish settlements are located along their mainland coast, as well as on towns on the Aegean islands.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The largest cities are Athens and Thessaloniki in Greece and İzmir in Turkey.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The most populated of the Aegean islands is Crete, followed by Euboea and Rhodes.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] Greece has established several marine protected areas along its coasts.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] According to the Network of Managers of Marine Protected Areas in the Mediterranean (MedPAN), four Greek MPAs are participating in the Network.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] These include Alonnisos Marine Park, while the Missolonghi–Aitoliko Lagoons and the island of Zakynthos are not on the Aegean.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The current coastline dates back to about 4000 BC.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] Before that time, at the peak of the last ice age (about 18,000 years ago) sea levels everywhere were 130 metres (430 ft) lower, and there were large well-watered coastal plains instead of much of the northern Aegean.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] When they were first occupied, the present-day islands including Milos with its important obsidian production were probably still connected to the mainland.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The present coastal arrangement appeared around 9,000 years ago, with post-ice age sea levels continuing to rise for another 3,000 years after that.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The subsequent Bronze Age civilizations of Greece and the Aegean Sea have given rise to the general term *Aegean civilization*.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] In ancient times, the sea was the birthplace of two ancient civilizations – the Minoans of Crete and the Mycenaeans of the Peloponnese.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The Minoan civilization was a Bronze Age civilization on the island of Crete and other Aegean islands, flourishing from around 3000 to 1450 BC before a period of decline, finally ending at around 1100 BC.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] It represented the first advanced civilization in Europe, leaving behind massive building complexes, tools, stunning artwork, writing systems, and a massive network of trade.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The Minoan period saw extensive trade between Crete, Aegean, and Mediterranean settlements, particularly the Near East.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The most notable Minoan palace is that of Knossos, followed by that of Phaistos.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The Mycenaean Greeks arose on the mainland, becoming the first advanced civilization in mainland Greece, which lasted from approximately 1600 to 1100 BC.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] It is believed that the site of Mycenae, which sits close to the Aegean coast, was the center of Mycenaean civilization.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The Mycenaeans introduced several innovations in the fields of engineering, architecture and military infrastructure, while trade over vast areas of the Mediterranean, including the Aegean, was essential for the Mycenaean economy.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] Their syllabic script, the Linear B, offers the first written records of the Greek language and their religion already included several deities that can also be found in the Olympic Pantheon.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] Mycenaean Greece was dominated by a warrior elite society and consisted of a network of palace-centered states that developed rigid hierarchical, political, social and economic systems.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] At the head of this society was the king, known as *wanax*.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The civilization of Mycenaean Greeks perished with the collapse of Bronze Age culture in the eastern Mediterranean, to be followed by the so-called Greek Dark Ages.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] It is undetermined what cause the collapse of the Mycenaeans.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] During the Greek Dark Ages, writing in the Linear B script ceased, vital trade links were lost, and towns and villages were abandoned.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The Archaic period followed the Greek Dark Ages in the 8th century BC.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] Greece became divided into small self-governing communities, and adopted the Phoenician alphabet, modifying it to create the Greek alphabet.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] By the 6th century BC several cities had emerged as dominant in Greek affairs: Athens, Sparta, Corinth, and Thebes, of which Athens, Sparta, and Corinth were closest to the Aegean Sea.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] Each of them had brought the surrounding rural areas and smaller towns under their control, and Athens and Corinth had become major maritime and mercantile powers as well.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] In the 8th and 7th centuries BC many Greeks migrated to form colonies in Magna Graecia (Southern Italy and Sicily), Asia Minor and further afield.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The Aegean Sea was the setting for one of the most pivotal naval engagements in history, when, on 20 September 480 B.C., the Athenian fleet gained a decisive victory over the Persian fleet of the Xerxes II of Persia at the Battle of Salamis.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] Thus ending any further attempt of western expansion by the Achaemenid Empire.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The Aegean Sea would later come to be under the control, albeit briefly, of the Kingdom of Macedonia.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] Philip II and his son Alexander the Great led a series of conquests that led not only to the unification of the Greek mainland and the control of the Aegean Sea under his rule, but also the destruction of the Achaemenid Empire.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] After Alexander the Great's death, his empire was divided among his generals.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] Cassander became king of the Hellenistic kingdom of Macedon, which held territory along the western coast of the Aegean, roughly corresponding to modern-day Greece.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The Kingdom of Lysimachus had control over the sea's eastern coast.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] Greece had entered the Hellenistic period.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The Macedonian Wars were a series of conflicts fought by the Roman Republic and its Greek allies in the eastern Mediterranean against several different major Greek kingdoms.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] They resulted in Roman control or influence over the eastern Mediterranean basin, including the Aegean, in addition to their hegemony in the western Mediterranean after the Punic Wars.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] During Roman rule, the land around the Aegean Sea fell under the provinces of Achaea, Macedonia, Thracia, Asia and Creta et Cyrenaica (island of Crete).
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The fall of the Western Roman Empire allowed its successor state, the Byzantine Empire, to continue Roman control over the Aegean Sea.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] However, their territory would later be threatened by the early Muslim conquests initiated by Muhammad in the 7th century.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] Although the Rashidun Caliphate did not manage to obtain land along the coast of the Aegean Sea, its conquest of the Eastern Anatolian peninsula as well as Egypt, the Levant, and North Africa left the Byzantine Empire weakened.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The Umayyad Caliphate expanded the territorial gains of the Rashidun Caliphate, conquering much of North Africa, and threatened the Byzantine Empire's control of Western Anatolia, where it meets the Aegean Sea.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] During the 820s, Crete was conquered by a group of Berbers Andalusians exiles led by Abu Hafs Umar al-Iqritishi, and it became an independent Islamic state.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The Byzantine Empire launched a campaign that took most of the island back in 842 and 843 under Theoktistos, but the re-conquest was not completed and was soon reversed.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] Later attempts by the Byzantine Empire to recover the island were without success.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] For the approximately 135 years of its existence, the emirate of Crete was one of the major foes of Byzantium.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] Crete commanded the sea lanes of the Eastern Mediterranean and functioned as a forward base and haven for Muslim corsair fleets that ravaged the Byzantine-controlled shores of the Aegean Sea.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] Crete returned to Byzantine rule under Nikephoros II Phokas, who launched a huge campaign against the Emirate of Crete in 960 to 961.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] Meanwhile, the Bulgarian Empire threatened Byzantine control of Northern Greece and the Aegean coast to the south.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] Under Presian and his successor Boris I, the Bulgarian Empire managed to obtain a small portion of the northern Aegean coast.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] Simeon I of Bulgaria led Bulgaria to its greatest territorial expansion, and managed to conqueror much of the northern and western coasts of the Aegean.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The Second Bulgarian Empire achieved similar success along, again, the northern and western coasts, under Ivan Asen II of Bulgaria.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The Seljuk Turks, under the Seljuk Empire, invaded the Byzantine Empire in 1068, from which they annexed almost all the territories of Anatolia, including the east coast of the Aegean Sea, during the reign of Alp Arslan, the second Sultan of the Seljuk Empire.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] After the death of his successor, Malik Shah I, the empire was divided, and Malik Shah was succeeded in Anatolia by Kilij Arslan I, who founded the Sultanate of Rum.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The Byzantines yet again recaptured the eastern coast of the Aegean.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The Venetians created the maritime state of the Duchy of the Archipelago, which included all the Cyclades except Mykonos and Tinos.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The Empire of Nicaea, a Byzantine rump state, managed to affect the Recapture of Constantinople from the Latins in 1261 and defeat Epirus.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] Byzantine successes were not to last; the Ottomans would conquer the area around the Aegean coast, but before their expansion the Byzantine Empire had already been weakened from internal conflict.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] By the late 14th century, the Byzantine Empire had lost all control of the coast of the Aegean Sea and could only exercise power around their capital, Constantinople.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The Ottoman Empire then gained control of all the Aegean coast with the exception of Crete, which was a Venetian colony until 1669.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The Greek War of Independence allowed a Greek state on the coast of the Aegean from 1829 onward.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] In the aftermath of the Balkan Wars (1912–1913) Greece expanded northwards along the coast, while Bulgaria gained access in the northernmost section of the sea.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The Ottoman Empire held a presence over the sea for over 500 years until its dissolution following World War I, when it was replaced by modern Turkey.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] After the war, Greece gained control over the area around the northern coast of the Aegean, including the territory held by Bulgaria.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] By the 1920s, Greece and Turkey had about resumed their present-day borders.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] In the Italo-Turkish War of 1912, Italy captured the Dodecanese islands, and had occupied them since, reneging on the 1919 Venizelos–Tittoni agreement to cede them to Greece.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The Greco-Italian War took place from October 1940 to April 1941 as part of the Balkans Campaign of World War II.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The Italian war aim was to establish a Greek puppet state, which would permit the Italian annexation of the Sporades and Cyclades islands in the Aegean Sea, to be administered as a part of the Italian Aegean Islands.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The German invasion resulted in the Axis occupation of Greece.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The German troops evacuated Athens on 12 October 1944, and by the end of the month, they had withdrawn from mainland Greece.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] Greece was then liberated by Allied troops.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] Many of the islands in the Aegean have safe harbours and bays.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] In ancient times, navigation through the sea was easier than travelling across the rough terrain of the Greek mainland, and to some extent, the coastal areas of Anatolia.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] Many of the islands are volcanic, and marble and iron are mined on other islands.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The larger islands have some fertile valleys and plains.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] Of the main islands in the Aegean Sea, two belong to Turkey – Bozcaada (Tenedos) and Gökçeada (Imbros); the rest belong to Greece.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] Between the two countries, there are political disputes over several aspects of political control over the Aegean space, including the size of territorial waters, air control and the delimitation of economic rights to the continental shelf.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] These issues are known as the Aegean dispute.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] Multiple ports are located along the Greek and Turkish coasts of the Aegean Sea.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The port of Piraeus in Athens is the chief port in Greece, the largest passenger port in Europe and the third largest in the world, servicing about 20 million passengers annually.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] With a throughput of 1.4 million TEUs, Piraeus is placed among the top ten ports in container traffic in Europe and the top container port in the Eastern Mediterranean.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] Piraeus is also the commercial hub of Greek shipping.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] Piraeus bi-annually acts as the focus for a major shipping convention, known as Posidonia, which attracts maritime industry professionals from all over the world.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] Piraeus is currently Greece's third-busiest port in terms of tons of goods transported, behind Agioi Theodoroi and Thessaloniki.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The central port serves ferry routes to almost every island in the eastern portion of Greece, the island of Crete, the Cyclades, the Dodecanese, and much of the northern and the eastern Aegean Sea, while the western part of the port is used for cargo services.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] As of 2007, the Port of Thessaloniki was the second-largest container port in Greece after the port of Piraeus, making it one of the busiest ports in Greece.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] In 2007, the Port of Thessaloniki handled 14,373,245 tonnes of cargo and 222,824 TEU's.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] Paloukia, on the island of Salamis, is a major passenger port.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] Fish are Greece's second-largest agricultural export, and Greece has Europe's largest fishing fleet.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] Fish captured include sardines, mackerel, grouper, grey mullets, sea bass, and seabream.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] There is a considerable difference between fish catches between the pelagic and demersal zones; with respect to pelagic fisheries, the catches from the northern, central and southern Aegean area groupings are dominated, respectively, by anchovy, horse mackerels, and boops.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] For demersal fisheries, the catches from the northern and southern Aegean area groupings are dominated by grey mullets and pickerel (*Spicara smaris*) respectively.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The industry has been impacted by the Great Recession.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] Overfishing and habitat destruction is also a concern, threatening grouper, and seabream populations, resulting in perhaps a 50% decline of fish catch.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] To address these concerns, Greek fishermen have been offered a compensation by the government.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] Although some species are defined as protected or threatened under EU legislation, several illegal species such as the molluscs *Pinna nobilis*, *Charonia tritonis* and *Lithophaga lithophaga*, can be bought in restaurants and fish markets around Greece.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The Aegean islands within the Aegean Sea are significant tourist destinations.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] Tourism to the Aegean islands contributes a significant portion of tourism in Greece, especially since the second half of the 20th century.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] A total of five UNESCO World Heritage sites are located the Aegean Islands; these include the Monastery of Saint John the Theologian and the Cave of the Apocalypse on Patmos, the Pythagoreion and Heraion of Samos in Samos, the Nea Moni of Chios, the island of Delos, and the Medieval City of Rhodes.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] Greece is one of the most visited countries in Europe and the world with over 33 million visitors in 2018, and the tourism industry around a quarter of Greece's Gross Domestic Product.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The islands of Santorini, Crete, Lesbos, Delos, and Mykonos are common tourist destinations.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] An estimated 2 million tourists visit Santorini annually.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] However, concerns relating to overtourism have arisen in recent years, such as issues of inadequate infrastructure and overcrowding.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] Alongside Greece, Turkey has also been successful in developing resort areas and attracting large number of tourists, contributing to tourism in Turkey.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The phrase "Blue Cruise" refers to recreational voyages along the Turkish Riviera, including across the Aegean.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The ancient city of Troy, a World Heritage Site, is on the Turkish coast of the Aegean.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] Greece and Turkey both take part in the Blue Flag beach certification programme of the Foundation for Environmental Education.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] The certification is awarded for beaches and marinas meeting strict quality standards including environmental protection, water quality, safety and services criteria.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] As of 2015, the Blue Flag has been awarded to 395 beaches and 9 marinas in Greece.
[src:antikythera-wreck/aegean-sea] Southern Aegean beaches on the Turkish coast include Muğla, with 102 beaches awarded with the blue flag, along with İzmir and Aydın, who have 49 and 30 beaches awarded respectively.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] An **amphora** (/ˈæmfərə/; Ancient Greek: ἀμφορεύς, romanized: **amphoreús**; English pl.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] **amphorae** or **amphoras**) is a type of storage and transport jar with a pointed bottom and characteristic shape and size which fit tightly (and therefore safely) against each other in storage rooms and packages, tied together with rope and delivered by land or sea.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] Vessels of similar size and shape have been used from as early as the Neolithic Period.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] Amphorae were used in vast numbers for the transport and storage of various products, both liquid and dry, but mostly for wine, olive oil, or garum.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] Transport amphorae are ceramic, but examples of table amphorae in metal, glass, and other materials have been found.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] Versions of the table amphorae were one of many shapes used in Ancient Greek vase painting.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] Two types of amphorae existed: table amphorae, and transport or storage amphorae.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] The amphora complements a large storage jar, the pithos (pl. pithoi), which makes available capacities between one-half and two and one-half tons.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] In contrast, the amphora holds under a half-ton, typically less than 50 kilograms (110 lb).
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] Where the pithos may have multiple small loops or lugs for fastening a rope harness, the amphora has two expansive handles joining the shoulder of the body and a long neck.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] The necks of pithoi are wide for scooping or bucket access.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] The necks of amphorae are narrow for pouring by a person holding it by the bottom and a handle.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] The size may require two or three handlers to lift.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] For the most part, however, an amphora was tableware, or sat close to the table, was intended to be seen, and was finely decorated as such by master painters.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] Stoppers made either of perishable materials, which have rarely survived, or of a refashioned potsherd, were used to seal the contents.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] Two principal types of amphorae existed: the *neck amphora*, in which the neck and body meet at a sharp angle; and the *one-piece amphora*, in which the neck and body form a continuous curve upwards.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] Neck amphorae were commonly used in the early history of ancient Greece, but were gradually replaced by the one-piece type from around the 7th century BC onward.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] Most were produced with a pointed base to allow upright storage by embedding in soft ground, such as sand.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] The base facilitated transport by ship, where the amphorae were packed upright or on their sides in as many as five staggered layers..
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] If upright, the bases probably were held by some sort of rack, and ropes passed through their handles to prevent shifting or toppling during rough seas.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] Heather and reeds might be used as packing around the vases.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] Racks could be used in kitchens and shops.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] The base also concentrated deposits from liquids with suspended solid particles, such as olive oil and wines.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] Amphorae are of great use to maritime archaeologists, as they often indicate the age of a shipwreck and the geographic origin of the cargo.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] They are occasionally so well preserved that the original content is still present, providing information on foodstuffs and mercantile systems.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] Amphorae were too cheap and plentiful to return to their origin-point and so, when empty, they were broken up at their destination.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] At a breakage site in Rome, Testaccio, close to the Tiber, the fragments, later wetted with calcium hydroxide (calce viva), remained to create a hill now named Monte Testaccio, 45 m (148 ft) high and more than 1 kilometre in circumference.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] Amphora is a Greco-Roman word developed in ancient Greek during the Bronze Age.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] The Romans acquired it during the Hellenization that occurred in the Roman Republic.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] Cato the Younger is the first known literary person to use it.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] The Romans turned the Greek form into a standard first declension noun, *amphora*, pl.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] The word and the vase were almost certainly introduced to Italy through the Greek settlements there, which traded extensively in Greek pottery.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] Even though the Etruscans imported, manufactured, and exported amphorae extensively in their wine industry, and other Greek vase names were Etruscanized, no Etruscan form of the word exists.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] There was perhaps an as yet unidentified native Etruscan word for the vase that pre-empted the adoption of *amphora*.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] The Latin word derived from the Greek *amphoreus* (ἀμφορεύς), a shortened form of *amphiphoreus* (ἀμφιφορεύς), a compound word combining *amphi-* ("on both sides", "twain") and *phoreus* ("carrier"), from *pherein* ("to carry"), referring to the vessel's two carrying handles on opposite sides.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] The amphora appears as 𐀀𐀠𐀡𐀩𐀸, *a-pi-po-re-we*, in the Linear B Bronze Age records of Knossos, 𐀀𐀡𐀩𐀸, *a-po-re-we*, at Mycenae, and the fragmentary *]-re-we* at Pylos, designated by Ideogram 209 𐃨, Bennett's AMPHORA, which has a number of scribal variants.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] The two spellings are transcriptions of amphiphorēwes (plural) and amphorēwe (dual) in Mycenaean Greek from which it may be seen that the short form prevailed on the mainland.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] Homer uses the long form for metrical reasons, and Herodotus has the short form.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] The largest stands as tall as 1.5 metres (4.9 feet) high, while some were less than 30 centimetres (12 inches) high - the smallest were called amphoriskoi (literally "little amphorae").
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] Most were around 45 centimetres (18 inches) high.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] There was a significant degree of standardisation in some variants; the wine amphora held a standard measure of about 39 litres (41 US qt), giving rise to the amphora quadrantal as a unit of measure in the Roman Empire.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] In all, approximately 66 distinct types of amphora have been identified.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] Further, the term also stands for an ancient Roman unit of measurement for liquids.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] The volume of a Roman amphora (*amphora quadrantal*) was about one cubic *pes* (foot), equivalent to 26.2 liters (5.8 imp gal; 6.9 U.S. gal).
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] Roman amphorae were wheel-thrown terracotta containers.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] During the production process the body was made first and then left to dry partially.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] Then coils of clay were added to form the neck, the rim, and the handles.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] Once the amphora was complete, the maker then treated the interior with resin that would prevent permeation of stored liquids.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] The reconstruction of these stages of production is based primarily on the study of modern amphora production in some areas of the eastern Mediterranean.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] Amphorae often were marked with a variety of stamps, sgraffito, and inscriptions.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] They provided information on the production, content, and subsequent marketing.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] A stamp usually was applied to the amphora at a partially dry stage.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] It indicates the name of the *figlina* (workshop) and/or the name of the owner of the workshop.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] Painted stamps, *tituli picti*, recorded the weight of the container and the contents, and were applied after the amphora was filled.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] Today, stamps are used to allow historians to track the flow of trade goods and recreate ancient trade networks.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] The first systematic classification of Roman amphorae types was undertaken by the German scholar Heinrich Dressel.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] Following the exceptional amphora deposit uncovered in Rome in Castro Pretorio at the end of the 1800s, he collected almost 200 inscriptions from amphorae and included them in the *Corpus Inscriptionum Latinarum*.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] In his studies of the amphora deposit he was the first to elaborate a classification of types, the so-called "Dressel table", which still is used today for many types.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] Subsequent studies on Roman amphorae have produced more detailed classifications, which usually are named after the scholar who studied them.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] For the neo-Phoenician types see the work by Maña published in 1951, and the revised classification by Van der Werff in 1977–1978.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] The Gallic amphorae have been studied by Laubenheimer in a study published in 1989, whereas the Cretan amphorae have been analyzed by Marangou-Lerat.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] Beltràn studied the Spanish types in 1970.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] Adriatic types have been studied by Lamboglia in 1955.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] For a general analysis of the Western Mediterranean types see Panella, and Peacock and Williams.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] Ceramics of shapes and uses falling within the range of amphorae, with or without handles, are of prehistoric heritage across Eurasia, from the Caucasus to China.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] Amphorae dated to approximately 4800 BC have been found in Banpo, a Neolithic site of the Yangshao culture in China.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] Amphorae first appeared on the Phoenician coast at approximately 3500 BC.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] In the Bronze and Iron Ages amphorae spread around the ancient Mediterranean world, being used by the ancient Greeks and Romans as the principal means for transporting and storing grapes, olive oil, wine, oil, olives, grain, fish, and other agricultural products.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] They were produced on an industrial scale until approximately the 7th century AD.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] Wooden and skin containers seem to have supplanted amphorae thereafter.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] They influenced Chinese ceramics and other East Asian ceramic cultures, especially as a fancy shape for high-quality decorative ceramics, and continued to be produced there long after they had ceased to be used further west.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] Besides coarse amphorae used for storage and transport, the vast majority, high-quality painted amphorae were produced in Ancient Greece in significant numbers for a variety of social and ceremonial purposes.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] Their design differs vastly from the more functional versions; they are typified by wide mouth and a ring base, with a glazed surface and decorated with figures or geometric shapes.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] They normally have a firm base on which they can stand.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] Panathenaic amphorae were used as prizes in the Panathenaic Festivals held between the 6th century BC to the 2nd century BC, filled with olive oil from a sacred grove.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] Surviving examples bear the inscription "I am one of the prizes from Athens", and usually depict the particular event they were awarded for.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] Painted amphorae were also used for funerary purposes, often in special types such as the *loutrophoros*.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] Especially in earlier periods, outsize vases were used as grave markers, while some amphorae were used as containers for the ashes of the dead.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] By the Roman period vase-painting had largely died out, and utilitarian amphorae were normally the only type produced.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] On a neck amphora, the handles are attached to the neck, which is separated from the belly by an angular carination.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] In contrast to the neck amphora, a belly amphora does not have a distinguished neck; instead, the belly reaches the mouth in a continuous curve.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] After the mid-5th century BC, this type was rarely produced.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] The *pelike* is a special type of belly amphora, with the belly placed lower, so that the widest point of the vessel is near its bottom.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] The *pelike* was introduced around the end of the 6th century BC.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] Another special type is the Panathenaic prize amphora, with black-figure decoration, produced exclusively as prize vessels for the Panathenaia and retaining the black-figure technique for centuries after the introduction of red-figure vase painting.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] Some examples bear the inscription "ΤΩΝ ΑΘΗΝΗΘΕΝ ΑΘΛΩΝ" meaning "[I am one] of the prizes from [the goddess] Athena".
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] They contained the prize of oil from the sacred olive tree of the goddess Athena for the winners of the athletic contests held to honour the goddess, and were evidently kept thereafter, and perhaps used to store wine, before being buried with the prize-winner.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] They depicted goddess Athena on one side (as seen on the second image on this page) and the athletic event on the other side, e.g. a scene of wrestling or running contest etc.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] By the Roman period utilitarian amphorae were normally the only type produced.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] The first type of Roman amphora, Dressel 1, appears in central Italy in the late 2nd century BC.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] This type had thick walls and a characteristic red fabric.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] It was very heavy, although also strong.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] Around the middle of the 1st century BC the so-called Dressel 2-4 started to become used widely.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] This type of amphora presented some advantages in being lighter and with thinner walls.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] It has been calculated that while a ship could accommodate approximately 4500 Dressel 1, it was possible to fit 6000 Dressel 2–4 in the same space.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] Dressel 2-4 were often produced in the same workshops used for the production of Dressel 1 which quickly ceased to be used.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] At the same time in Cuma (southern Italy) the production of the *cadii cumani* type starts (Dressel 21–22).
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] These containers were mainly used for the transportation of fruit and were used until the middle imperial period.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] At the same time, in central Italy, the so-called Spello amphorae, small containers, were produced for the transportation of wine.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] On the Adriatic coast the older types were replaced by the Lamboglia 2 type, a wine amphora commonly produced between the end of the 2nd and the 1st century BC.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] This type developed later into the Dressel 6A which becomes dominant during Augustan times.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] In the Gallic provinces the first examples of Roman amphorae were local imitations of preexisting types such as Dressel 1, Dressel 2–4, Pascual 1, and Haltern 70.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] The more typical Gallic production begins within the ceramic ateliers in Marseille during late Augustan times.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] The type Oberaden 74 was produced to such an extent that it influenced the production of some Italic types.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] Spanish amphorae became particularly popular thanks to a flourishing production phase in late Republican times.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] The *Hispania Baetica* and *Hispania Tarraconensis* regions (south-western and eastern Spain) were the main production areas between the 2nd and the 1st century BC due to the distribution of land to military veterans and the founding of new colonies.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] Spanish amphorae were widespread in the Mediterranean area during early imperial times.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] The most common types were all produced in Baetica and among these there were the Dressel 20, a typical olive oil container, the Dressel 7–13, for garum (fish sauce), and the Haltern 70, for defrutum (fruit sauce).
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] In the Tarraconensis region the Pascual 1 was the most common type, a wine amphora shaped on the Dressel 1, and imitations of Dressel 2–4.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] North-African production was based on an ancient tradition which may be traced back to the Phoenician colony of Carthage.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] Phoenician amphorae had characteristic small handles attached directly onto the upper body.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] This feature becomes the distinctive mark of late-Republican/early imperial productions, which are then called neo-Phoenician.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] The types produced in Tripolitania and Northern Tunisia are the Maña C1 and C2, later renamed Van der Werff 1, 2, and 3.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] In the Aegean area the types from the island of Rhodes were quite popular starting from the 3rd century BC due to local wine production which flourished over a long period.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] These types developed into the *Camulodunum* 184, an amphora used for the transportation of Rhodian wine all over the empire.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] Imitations of the Dressel 2-4 were produced on the island of Cos for the transportation of wine from the 4th century BC until middle imperial times.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] Cretan containers also were popular for the transportation of wine and can be found around the Mediterranean from Augustan times until the 3rd century AD.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] During the late imperial period (3rd - 7th centuries AD), north-African types dominated amphora production in the west Mediterranean.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] The so-called African I and II types were widely used from the 2nd until the late 4th century AD.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] Production of Hispanic, Gallic, and Italic amphorae decreased greatly in the 5th and 6th centuries.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] In the east Mediterranean, several different varieties became extremely popular and nearly ubiquitous.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] The Late Roman Amphora (LRA) 1 amphora was produced in Cilicia and Cypress, and traded all throughout the Mediterranean from the 5th to 6th centuries.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] Other types from the eastern Mediterranean (Gaza), such as the so-called Late Roman 4, became very popular between the 4th and the 7th century AD, while Italic productions ceased.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] The largest known wreck of an amphorae cargo ship, carrying 6,000 pots, was discovered off the coast of Kefalonia, an Ionian island off the coast of Greece.
[src:antikythera-wreck/amphora] Some modern winemakers and brewers use amphorae to provide a different palate and taste to their products from those that are available with other aging methods.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] An **analog computer** or **analogue computer** is a type of computation machine (computer) that uses physical phenomena such as electrical, mechanical, or hydraulic quantities behaving according to the mathematical principles in question (*analog signals*) to model the problem being solved.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] In contrast, digital computers represent varying quantities symbolically and by discrete values of both time and amplitude (digital signals).
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Analog computers can have a very wide range of complexity.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Slide rules and nomograms are the simplest, while naval gunfire control computers and large hybrid digital/analog computers were among the most complicated.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Complex mechanisms for process control and protective relays used analog computation to perform control and protective functions.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] The common property of all of them is that they don't use algorithms to determine the fashion of how the computer works.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] They rather use a structure analogous to the system to be solved (a so called analogon, model or analogy) which is also eponymous to the term analog computer, because they represent a model.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Perhaps the most relatable example of analog computers are mechanical watches where the continuous and periodic rotation of interlinked gears drives the second, minute and hour needles in the clock.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] More complex applications, such as aircraft flight simulators and synthetic-aperture radar, remained the domain of analog computing (and hybrid computing) well into the 1980s, since digital computers were insufficient for the task.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] This is a list of examples of early computation devices considered precursors of the modern computers.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Some of them may even have been dubbed 'computers' by the press, though they may fail to fit modern definitions.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] The Antikythera mechanism, a type of device used to determine the positions of heavenly bodies known as an orrery, was described as an early mechanical analog computer by British physicist, information scientist, and historian of science Derek J. de Solla Price.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] It was discovered in 1901, in the Antikythera wreck off the Greek island of Antikythera, between Kythera and Crete, and has been dated to c.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] 150~100 BC, during the Hellenistic period.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Devices of a level of complexity comparable to that of the Antikythera mechanism would not reappear until a thousand years later.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Many mechanical aids to calculation and measurement were constructed for astronomical and navigation use.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] The planisphere was first described by Ptolemy in the 2nd century AD.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] The astrolabe was invented in the Hellenistic world in either the 1st or 2nd centuries BC and is often attributed to Hipparchus.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] A combination of the planisphere and dioptra, the astrolabe was effectively an analog computer capable of working out several different kinds of problems in spherical astronomy.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] The sector, a calculating instrument used for solving problems in proportion, trigonometry, multiplication and division, and for various functions, such as squares and cube roots, was developed in the late 16th century and found application in gunnery, surveying and navigation.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] The planimeter was a manual instrument to calculate the area of a closed figure by tracing over it with a mechanical linkage.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] The slide rule was invented around 1620–1630, shortly after the publication of the concept of the logarithm.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] It is a hand-operated analog computer for doing multiplication and division.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] As slide rule development progressed, added scales provided reciprocals, squares and square roots, cubes and cube roots, as well as transcendental functions such as logarithms and exponentials, circular and hyperbolic trigonometry and other functions.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Slide rules have been largely rendered obsolete by electronic calculators, though purpose-built variants persist in some niches, notably the E6-B flight computer for pilot training.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] In 1831–1835, mathematician and engineer Giovanni Plana devised a perpetual-calendar machine, which, through a system of pulleys and cylinders, could predict the perpetual calendar for every year from AD 0 (that is, 1 BC) to AD 4000, keeping track of leap years and varying day length.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] The tide-predicting machine invented by Sir William Thomson in 1872 was of great utility to navigation in shallow waters.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] It used a system of pulleys and wires to automatically calculate predicted tide levels for a set period at a particular location.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] The differential analyser, a mechanical analog computer designed to solve differential equations by integration, used wheel-and-disc mechanisms to perform the integration.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] In 1876 James Thomson had already discussed the possible construction of such calculators, but he had been stymied by the limited output torque of the ball-and-disk integrators.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] This work led to the mathematical understanding of the Gibbs phenomenon of overshoot in Fourier representation near discontinuities.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] In a differential analyzer, the output of one integrator drove the input of the next integrator, or a graphing output.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] The torque amplifier was the advance that allowed these machines to work.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Starting in the 1920s, Vannevar Bush and others developed mechanical differential analyzers.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] The Dumaresq was a mechanical calculating device invented around 1902 by Lieutenant John Dumaresq of the Royal Navy.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] It was an analog computer that related vital variables of the fire control problem to the movement of one's own ship and that of a target ship.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] It was often used with other devices, such as a Vickers range clock to generate range and deflection data so the gun sights of the ship could be continuously set.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] A number of versions of the Dumaresq were produced of increasing complexity as development proceeded.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] By 1912, Arthur Pollen had developed an electrically driven mechanical analog computer for fire-control systems, based on the differential analyser.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] It was used by the Imperial Russian Navy in World War I.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Starting in 1929, AC network analyzers were constructed to solve calculation problems related to electrical power systems that were too large to solve with numerical methods at the time.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] These were essentially scale models of the electrical properties of the full-size system.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Since network analyzers could handle problems too large for analytic methods or hand computation, they were also used to solve problems in nuclear physics and in the design of structures.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] More than 50 large network analyzers were built by the end of the 1950s.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] World War II era gun directors, gun data computers, and bomb sights used mechanical analog computers.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] In 1942 Helmut Hölzer built a fully electronic analog computer at Peenemünde Army Research Center as an embedded control system (*mixing device*) to calculate V-2 rocket trajectories from the accelerations and orientations (measured by gyroscopes) and to stabilize and guide the missile.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Mechanical analog computers were very important in gun fire control in World War II, the Korean War and well past the Vietnam War; they were made in significant numbers.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] In the period 1930–1945 in the Netherlands, Johan van Veen developed an analogue computer to calculate and predict tidal currents when the geometry of the channels are changed.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Around 1950, this idea was developed into the Deltar, a hydraulic analogy computer supporting the closure of estuaries in the southwest of the Netherlands (the Delta Works).
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] The FERMIAC was an analog computer invented by physicist Enrico Fermi in 1947 to aid in his studies of neutron transport.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Project Cyclone was an analog computer developed by Reeves in 1950 for the analysis and design of dynamic systems.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Project Typhoon was an analog computer developed by RCA in 1952.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] It consisted of over 4,000 electron tubes and used 100 dials and 6,000 plug-in connectors to program.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] The MONIAC Computer was a hydraulic analogy of a national economy first unveiled in 1949.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Computer Engineering Associates was spun out of Caltech in 1950 to provide commercial services using the "Direct Analogy Electric Analog Computer" ("the largest and most impressive general-purpose analyzer facility for the solution of field problems") developed there by Gilbert D.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Educational analog computers illustrated the principles of analog calculation.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] The Heathkit EC-1, a $199 educational analog computer, was made by the Heath Company, US c.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] It was programmed using patch cords that connected nine operational amplifiers and other components.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] The relative resistance of the potentiometer was then equivalent to the formula of the equation being solved.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Multiplication or division could be performed, depending on which dials were inputs and which was the output.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Accuracy and resolution was limited and a simple slide rule was more accurate.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] However, the unit did demonstrate the basic principle.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Analog computer designs were published in electronics magazines.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] One example is the PEAC (Practical Electronics analogue computer), published in *Practical Electronics* in the January 1968 edition.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Another more modern hybrid computer design was published in *Everyday Practical Electronics* in 2002.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] An example described in the EPE hybrid computer was the flight of a VTOL aircraft such as the Harrier jump jet.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] The altitude and speed of the aircraft were calculated by the analog part of the computer and sent to a PC via a digital microprocessor and displayed on the PC screen.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] In industrial process control, analog loop controllers were used to automatically regulate temperature, flow, pressure, or other process conditions.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] The technology of these controllers ranged from purely mechanical integrators, through vacuum-tube and solid-state devices, to emulation of analog controllers by microprocessors.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] The similarity between linear mechanical components, such as springs and dashpots (viscous-fluid dampers), and electrical components, such as capacitors, inductors, and resistors is striking in terms of mathematics.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] They can be modeled using equations of the same form.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] However, the difference between these systems is what makes analog computing useful.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Complex systems often are not amenable to pen-and-paper analysis, and require some form of testing or simulation.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Complex mechanical systems, such as suspensions for racing cars, are expensive to fabricate and hard to modify.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] And taking precise mechanical measurements during high-speed tests adds further difficulty.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] By contrast, it is very inexpensive to build an electrical equivalent of a complex mechanical system, to simulate its behavior.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Engineers arrange a few operational amplifiers (op amps) and some passive linear components to form a circuit that follows the same equations as the mechanical system being simulated.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] All measurements can be taken directly with an oscilloscope.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] In the circuit, the (simulated) stiffness of the spring, for instance, can be changed by adjusting the parameters of an integrator.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] The electrical system is an analogy to the physical system, hence the name, but it is much less expensive than a mechanical prototype, much easier to modify, and generally safer.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] The electronic circuit can also be made to run faster or slower than the physical system being simulated.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Experienced users of electronic analog computers said that they offered a comparatively intimate control and understanding of the problem, relative to digital simulations.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Electronic analog computers are especially well-suited to representing situations described by differential equations.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Historically, they were often used when a system of differential equations proved very difficult to solve by traditional means.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] As a simple example, the dynamics of a spring-mass system can be described by the equation $m{\ddot {y}}+d{\dot {y}}+cy=mg$ , with y as the vertical position of a mass m , d the damping coefficient, c the spring constant and g the gravity of Earth.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] The equivalent analog circuit consists of two integrators for the state variables $-{\dot {y}}$ (speed) and y (position), one inverter, and three potentiometers.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Electronic analog computers have drawbacks: the value of the circuit's supply voltage limits the range over which the variables may vary (since the value of a variable is represented by a voltage on a particular wire).
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Therefore, each problem must be scaled so its parameters and dimensions can be represented using voltages that the circuit can supply —e.g., the expected magnitudes of the velocity and the position of a spring pendulum.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Improperly scaled variables can have their values "clamped" by the limits of the supply voltage.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Or if scaled too small, they can suffer from higher noise levels.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Either problem can cause the circuit to produce an incorrect simulation of the physical system.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] The precision of the analog computer readout was limited chiefly by the precision of the readout equipment used, generally three or four significant figures.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] (Modern digital simulations are much better in this area.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Digital arbitrary-precision arithmetic can provide any desired degree of precision.) However, in most cases the precision of an analog computer is absolutely sufficient given the uncertainty of the model characteristics and its technical parameters.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] In the US during the 1960s, the major manufacturer was Electronic Associates of Princeton, New Jersey, with its 231R Analog Computer (vacuum tubes, 20 integrators) and subsequently its EAI 8800 Analog Computer (solid state operational amplifiers, 64 integrators).
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Its challenger was Applied Dynamics of Ann Arbor, Michigan.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] On the patch panel, various connections and routes can be set and switched to configure the machine and determine signal flows.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] This allows users to flexibly configure and reconfigure the analog computing system to perform specific tasks.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Patch panels are used to control data flows, connect and disconnect connections between various blocks of the system, including signal sources, amplifiers, filters, and other components.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] They provide convenience and flexibility in configuring and experimenting with analog computations.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Patch panels can be presented as a physical panel with connectors or, in more modern systems, as a software interface that allows virtual management of signal connections and routes.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Output devices in analog machines can vary depending on the specific goals of the system.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] For example, they could be graphical indicators, oscilloscopes, graphic recording devices, TV connection module, voltmeter, etc.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] These devices allow for the visualization of analog signals and the representation of the results of measurements or mathematical operations.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] These are just general blocks that can be found in a typical analog computing machine.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] The actual configuration and components may vary depending on the specific implementation and the intended use of the machine.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Analog computing devices are fast; digital computing devices are more versatile and accurate.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] The idea behind an analog-digital hybrid is to combine the two processes for the best efficiency.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] An example of such hybrid elementary device is the hybrid multiplier, where one input is an analog signal, the other input is a digital signal and the output is analog.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] It acts as an analog potentiometer, upgradable digitally.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] This kind of hybrid technique is mainly used for fast dedicated real time computation when computing time is very critical, as signal processing for radars and generally for controllers in embedded systems.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] In the early 1970s, analog computer manufacturers tried to tie together their analog computers with a digital computers to get the advantages of the two techniques.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] In such systems, the digital computer controlled the analog computer, providing initial set-up, initiating multiple analog runs, and automatically feeding and collecting data.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] The digital computer may also participate to the calculation itself using analog-to-digital and digital-to-analog converters.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] The largest manufacturer of hybrid computers was Electronic Associates.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Their hybrid computer model 8900 was made of a digital computer and one or more analog consoles.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] These systems were mainly dedicated to large projects such as the Apollo program and Space Shuttle at NASA, or Ariane in Europe, especially during the integration step where at the beginning everything is simulated, and progressively real components replace their simulated parts.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Only one company was known as offering general commercial computing services on its hybrid computers, CISI of France, in the 1970s.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] The best reference in this field is the 100,000 simulation runs for each certification of the automatic landing systems of Airbus and Concorde aircraft.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] After 1980, purely digital computers progressed more and more rapidly and were fast enough to compete with analog computers.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] One key to the speed of analog computers was their fully parallel computation, but this was also a limitation.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] The more equations required for a problem, the more analog components were needed, even when the problem wasn't time critical.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] "Programming" a problem meant interconnecting the analog operators; even with a removable wiring panel this was not very versatile.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Throughout history, many types of mechanical analog computers have been invented.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] These ranged from simple devices (like planimeters) to complex fire-control systems that guided WWII naval guns.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Practical mechanical analog computers of any significant complexity used rotating shafts to carry variables from one mechanism to another.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Cables and pulleys were used in a Fourier synthesizer, a tide-predicting machine, which summed the individual harmonic components.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Another category, not nearly as well known, used rotating shafts only for input and output, with precision racks and pinions.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] The racks were connected to linkages that performed the computation.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Naval sonar fire control computer of the later 1950s, made by Librascope, was of this type, as was the principal computer in the Mk.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] These computers often employed precision miter-gear differentials (pairs of bevel gears arranged to produce the sum or difference of two shaft rotations) to transmit variables between computing elements.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] The Ford Instrument Mark I Fire Control Computer, for example, contained approximately 160 miter-gear differentials.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Integration with respect to another variable was done by a rotating disc driven by one variable.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Output came from a pick-off device (such as a wheel) positioned at a radius on the disc proportional to the second variable.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] (A carrier with a pair of steel balls supported by small rollers worked especially well.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] A roller, its axis parallel to the disc's surface, provided the output.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Arbitrary functions of one variable were provided by cams, with gearing to convert follower movement to shaft rotation.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Functions of two variables were provided by three-dimensional cams.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] In one good design, one of the variables rotated the cam.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] A hemispherical follower moved its carrier on a pivot axis parallel to that of the cam's rotating axis.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] The second variable moved the follower along the axis of the cam.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] One practical application was ballistics in gunnery.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Coordinate conversion from polar to rectangular was done by a mechanical resolver (called a "component solver" in US Navy fire control computers).
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Two discs on a common axis positioned a sliding block with pin (stubby shaft) on it.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] One disc was a face cam, and a follower on the block in the face cam's groove set the radius.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] The other disc, closer to the pin, contained a straight slot in which the block moved.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] The input angle rotated the latter disc (the face cam disc, for an unchanging radius, rotated with the other (angle) disc; a differential and a few gears did this correction).
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Referring to the mechanism's frame, the location of the pin corresponded to the tip of the vector represented by the angle and magnitude inputs.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Rectilinear-coordinate outputs (both sine and cosine, typically) came from two slotted plates, each slot fitting on the block just mentioned.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] The plates moved in straight lines, the movement of one plate at right angles to that of the other.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] The slots were at right angles to the direction of movement.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Each plate, by itself, was like a Scotch yoke, known to steam engine enthusiasts.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] During World War II, a similar mechanism converted rectilinear to polar coordinates, but it was not particularly successful and was eliminated in a significant redesign (USN, Mk.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Multiplication was done by mechanisms based on the geometry of similar right triangles.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Using the trigonometric terms for a right triangle, specifically opposite, adjacent, and hypotenuse, the adjacent side was fixed by construction.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] One variable changed the magnitude of the opposite side.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] In many cases, this variable changed sign; the hypotenuse could coincide with the adjacent side (a zero input), or move beyond the adjacent side, representing a sign change.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Typically, a pinion-operated rack moving parallel to the (trig.-defined) opposite side would position a slide with a slot coincident with the hypotenuse.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] A pivot on the rack let the slide's angle change freely.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] At the other end of the slide (the angle, in trig. terms), a block on a pin fixed to the frame defined the vertex between the hypotenuse and the adjacent side.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] At any distance along the adjacent side, a line perpendicular to it intersects the hypotenuse at a particular point.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] The distance between that point and the adjacent side is some fraction that is the product of *1* the distance from the vertex, and *2* the magnitude of the opposite side.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] The second input variable in this type of multiplier positions a slotted plate perpendicular to the adjacent side.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] That slot contains a block, and that block's position in its slot is determined by another block right next to it.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] The latter slides along the hypotenuse, so the two blocks are positioned at a distance from the (trig.) adjacent side by an amount proportional to the product.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] To provide the product as an output, a third element, another slotted plate, also moves parallel to the (trig.) opposite side of the theoretical triangle.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] As usual, the slot is perpendicular to the direction of movement.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] A block in its slot, pivoted to the hypotenuse block positions it.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] A special type of integrator, used at a point where only moderate accuracy was needed, was based on a steel ball, instead of a disc.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] It had two inputs, one to rotate the ball, and the other to define the angle of the ball's rotating axis.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] That axis was always in a plane that contained the axes of two movement pick-off rollers, quite similar to the mechanism of a rolling-ball computer mouse (in that mechanism, the pick-off rollers were roughly the same diameter as the ball).
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] The pick-off roller axes were at right angles.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] A pair of rollers "above" and "below" the pick-off plane were mounted in rotating holders that were geared together.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] That gearing was driven by the angle input, and established the rotating axis of the ball.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] The other input rotated the "bottom" roller to make the ball rotate.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Essentially, the whole mechanism, called a component integrator, was a variable-speed drive with one motion input and two outputs, as well as an angle input.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] The angle input varied the ratio (and direction) of coupling between the "motion" input and the outputs according to the sine and cosine of the input angle.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Other readout mechanisms, not directly part of the computation, included internal odometer-like counters with interpolating drum dials for indicating internal variables, and mechanical multi-turn limit stops.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Electronic analog computers typically have front panels with numerous jacks (single-contact sockets) that permit patch cords (flexible wires with plugs at both ends) to create the interconnections that define the problem setup.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] In addition, there are precision high-resolution potentiometers (variable resistors) for setting up (and, when needed, varying) scale factors.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] In addition, there is usually a zero-center analog pointer-type meter for modest-accuracy voltage measurement.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Stable, accurate voltage sources provide known magnitudes.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Typical electronic analog computers contain anywhere from a few to a hundred or more operational amplifiers ("op amps"), named because they perform mathematical operations.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Op amps are a particular type of feedback amplifier with very high gain and stable input (low and stable offset).
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] They are always used with precision feedback components that, in operation, all but cancel out the currents arriving from input components.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] The majority of op amps in a representative setup are summing amplifiers, which add and subtract analog voltages, providing the result at their output jacks.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] As well, op amps with capacitor feedback are usually included in a setup; they integrate the sum of their inputs with respect to time.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Integrating with respect to another variable is the nearly exclusive province of mechanical analog integrators; it is almost never done in electronic analog computers.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] However, given that a problem solution does not change with time, time can serve as one of the variables.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Other computing elements include analog multipliers, nonlinear function generators, and analog comparators.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Electrical elements such as inductors and capacitors used in electrical analog computers had to be carefully manufactured to reduce non-ideal effects.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] For example, in the construction of AC power network analyzers, one motive for using higher frequencies for the calculator (instead of the actual power frequency) was that higher-quality inductors could be more easily made.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Many general-purpose analog computers avoided the use of inductors entirely, re-casting the problem in a form that could be solved using only resistive and capacitive elements, since high-quality capacitors are relatively easy to make.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] The use of electrical properties in analog computers means that calculations are normally performed in real time (or faster), at a speed determined mostly by the frequency response of the operational amplifiers and other computing elements.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] In the history of electronic analog computers, there were some special high-speed types.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Nonlinear functions and calculations can be constructed to a limited precision (three or four digits) by designing function generators—special circuits of various combinations of resistors and diodes to provide the nonlinearity.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Typically, as the input voltage increases, progressively more diodes conduct.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] When compensated for temperature, the forward voltage drop of a transistor's base-emitter junction can provide a usably accurate logarithmic or exponential function.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Op amps scale the output voltage so that it is usable with the rest of the computer.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Any physical process that models some computation can be interpreted as an analog computer.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] These are all described in Dewdney (1984).
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Analog computers often have a complicated framework, but they have, at their core, a set of key components that perform the calculations.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] The operator manipulates these through the computer's framework.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Key hydraulic components might include pipes, valves and containers.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Key mechanical components might include rotating shafts for carrying data within the computer, miter gear differentials, disc/ball/roller integrators, cams (2-D and 3-D), mechanical resolvers and multipliers, and torque servos.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] In some analog computer designs, multiplication is much preferred to division.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Division is carried out with a multiplier in the feedback path of an Operational Amplifier.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Differentiation with respect to time is not frequently used, and in practice is avoided by redefining the problem when possible.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] It corresponds in the frequency domain to a high-pass filter, which means that high-frequency noise is amplified; differentiation also risks instability.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] In general, analog computers are limited by non-ideal effects.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] An analog signal is composed of four basic components: DC and AC magnitudes, frequency, and phase.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] The real limits of range on these characteristics limit analog computers.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Some of these limits include the operational amplifier offset, finite gain, and frequency response, noise floor, non-linearities, temperature coefficient, and parasitic effects within semiconductor devices.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] For commercially available electronic components, ranges of these aspects of input and output signals are always figures of merit.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] In the 1950s to 1970s, digital computers based on first vacuum tubes, transistors, integrated circuits and then micro-processors became more economical and precise.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] This led digital computers to largely replace analog computers.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Even so, some research in analog computation is still being done.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] A few universities still use analog computers to teach control system theory.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] The American company Comdyna manufactured small analog computers.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] At Indiana University Bloomington, Jonathan Mills has developed the Extended Analog Computer based on sampling voltages in a foam sheet.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] At the Harvard Robotics Laboratory, analog computation is a research topic.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Lyric Semiconductor's error correction circuits use analog probabilistic signals.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Slide rules are still used as flight computers in flight training.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] With the development of very-large-scale integration (VLSI) technology, Yannis Tsividis' group at Columbia University has been revisiting analog/hybrid computers design in standard CMOS process.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Two VLSI chips have been developed, an 80th-order analog computer (250 nm) by Glenn Cowan in 2005 and a 4th-order hybrid computer (65 nm) developed by Ning Guo in 2015, both targeting at energy-efficient ODE/PDE applications.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Glenn's chip contains 16 macros, in which there are 25 analog computing blocks, namely integrators, multipliers, fanouts, few nonlinear blocks.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Ning's chip contains one macro block, in which there are 26 computing blocks including integrators, multipliers, fanouts, ADCs, SRAMs and DACs.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Arbitrary nonlinear function generation is made possible by the ADC+SRAM+DAC chain, where the SRAM block stores the nonlinear function data.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] In 2016, a team of researchers developed a compiler to solve differential equations using analog circuits.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Analog computers are also used in neuromorphic computing, and in 2021 a group of researchers have shown that a specific type of artificial neural network called a spiking neural network was able to work with analog neuromorphic computers.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] In 2021, the German company anabrid GmbH began to produce THE ANALOG THING (abbreviated THAT), a small low-cost analog computer mainly for educational and scientific use.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] The company is also constructing analog mainframes and hybrid computers.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] Analog (audio) synthesizers can also be viewed as a form of analog computer, and their technology was originally based in part on electronic analog computer technology.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] The ARP 2600's Ring Modulator was actually a moderate-accuracy analog multiplier.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] The Simulation Council (or Simulations Council) was an association of analog computer users in US.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] It is now known as The Society for Modeling and Simulation International.
[src:antikythera-wreck/analog-computer] The Simulation Council newsletters from 1952 to 1963 are available online and show the concerns and technologies at the time, and the common use of analog computers for missilry.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] In modern historiography, **ancient Rome** is the Roman civilisation from the founding of the Italian city of Rome in the 8th century BC to the collapse of the Western Roman Empire in the 5th century AD.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] It encompasses the Roman Kingdom (753–509 BC), the Roman Republic (509‍–‍27 BC), and the Roman Empire (27 BC – 476 AD) until the fall of the western empire.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Ancient Rome began as an Italic settlement, traditionally dated to 753 BC, beside the River Tiber in the Italian Peninsula.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The settlement grew into the city and polity of Rome, and came to control its neighbours through a combination of treaties and military strength.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] It eventually controlled the Italian Peninsula, assimilating the Greek culture of southern Italy (Magna Graecia) and the Etruscan culture, and then became the dominant power in the Mediterranean region and parts of Europe.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] At its height it controlled the North African coast, Egypt, Southern Europe, and most of Western Europe, the Balkans, Crimea, and much of the Middle East, including Anatolia, the Levant, and parts of Mesopotamia and Arabia.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] That empire was among the largest empires in the ancient world, covering around 5 million square kilometres (1.9 million square miles) in AD 117, with an estimated 50 to 90 million inhabitants, roughly 20% of the world's population at the time.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The Roman state evolved from an elective monarchy to a classical republic and then to an increasingly autocratic military dictatorship during the Empire.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Ancient Rome is often grouped into classical antiquity together with ancient Greece, and their similar cultures and societies are known as the Greco-Roman world.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Ancient Roman civilisation has contributed to modern language, religion, society, technology, law, politics, government, warfare, art, literature, architecture, and engineering.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Rome professionalised and expanded its military and created a system of government called *res publica*, the inspiration for modern republics such as the United States and France.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] It achieved impressive technological and architectural feats, such as the empire-wide construction of aqueducts and roads, as well as more grandiose monuments and facilities.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Archaeological evidence of settlement around Rome starts to emerge c.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Large-scale organisation appears only c.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] 800 BC, with the first graves in the Esquiline Hill's necropolis, along with a clay and timber wall on the bottom of the Palatine Hill dating to the middle of the 8th century BC.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] 650 BC, the Romans started to drain the valley between the Capitoline and Palatine Hills, where today sits the Roman Forum.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] By the 6th century BC, the Romans were constructing the Temple of Jupiter Optimus Maximus on the Capitoline and expanding to the Forum Boarium located between the Capitoline and Aventine Hills.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The Romans themselves had a founding myth, attributing their city to Romulus and Remus, offspring of Mars and a princess of the mythical city of Alba Longa.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The sons, sentenced to death, were rescued by a wolf and returned to restore the Alban king and found a city.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] After a dispute, Romulus killed Remus and became the city's sole founder.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The area of his initial settlement on the Palatine Hill was later known as Roma quadrata ('Square Rome').
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The story dates at least to the 3rd century BC, and the later Roman antiquarian Marcus Terentius Varro placed the city's foundation to 753 BC.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Another legend, recorded by Greek historian Dionysius of Halicarnassus, says that Prince Aeneas led a group of Trojans on a sea voyage to found a new Troy after the Trojan War.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] They landed on the banks of the Tiber River and a woman travelling with them, Roma, torched their ships to prevent them from leaving again.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The Roman poet Virgil recounted this legend in his classical epic poem the *Aeneid*.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Literary and archaeological evidence is clear on there having been kings in Rome, attested in fragmentary 6th-century BC texts.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Long after the abolition of the Roman monarchy, a vestigial *rex sacrorum* was retained to exercise the monarch's former priestly functions.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The Romans believed that their monarchy was elective, with seven legendary kings who were largely unrelated by blood.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Evidence of Roman expansion is clear in the 6th century BC; by its end, Rome controlled a territory of some 780 square kilometres (300 square miles) with a population perhaps as high as 35,000.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] 625 BC; the Romans attributed the creation of their first popular organisations and the Senate to the regal period as well.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Rome also started to extend its control over its Latin neighbours.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] While later Roman stories like the *Aeneid* asserted that all Latins descended from the character Aeneas, a common culture is attested to archaeologically.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Attested to reciprocal rights of marriage and citizenship between Latin cities—the *Jus Latii*—along with shared religious festivals, further indicate a shared culture.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] By the end of the 6th century, most of this area had become dominated by the Romans.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] By the end of the 6th century BC, Rome and many of its Italian neighbours entered a period of turbulence.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Archaeological evidence implies some degree of large-scale warfare.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] According to tradition and later writers such as Livy, the Roman Republic was established c.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] 509 BC, when the last of the seven kings of Rome, Tarquin the Proud, was deposed and a system based on annually elected magistrates and various representative assemblies was established.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] A constitution set a series of checks and balances, and a separation of powers.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The most important magistrates were the two consuls, who together exercised executive authority such as *imperium*, or military command.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The consuls had to work with the Senate, which was initially an advisory council of the ranking nobility, or patricians, but grew in size and power.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Other magistrates of the Republic include tribunes, quaestors, aediles, praetors and censors.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The magistracies were originally restricted to patricians, but were later opened to common people, or plebeians.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Republican voting assemblies included the *comitia centuriata* ('centuriate assembly'), which voted on matters of war and peace and elected men to the most important offices, and the *comitia tributa* ('tribal assembly'), which elected less important offices.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] In the 4th century BC, Rome had come under attack by the Gauls, who now extended their power in the Italian peninsula beyond the Po Valley and through Etruria.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] On 16 July 390 BC, a Gallic army under the leadership of tribal chieftain Brennus, defeated the Romans at the Battle of the Allia and marched to Rome.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The Gauls looted and burned the city, then laid siege to the Capitoline Hill, where some Romans had barricaded themselves, for seven months.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The Gauls then agreed to give the Romans peace in exchange for 1000 pounds of gold.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] According to later legend, the Roman supervising the weighing noticed that the Gauls were using false scales.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The Romans then took up arms and defeated the Gauls.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The Romans gradually subdued the other peoples on the Italian peninsula, including the Etruscans.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The last threat to Roman hegemony in Italy came when Tarentum, a major Greek colony, enlisted the aid of Pyrrhus of Epirus in 281 BC, but this effort failed as well.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The Romans secured their conquests by founding Roman colonies in strategic areas, thereby establishing stable control over the region.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] In the 3rd century BC Rome faced a new and formidable opponent: Carthage, the other major power in the Western Mediterranean.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The First Punic War began in 264 BC, when the city of Messana asked for Carthage's help in their conflicts with Hiero II of Syracuse.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] After the Carthaginian intercession, Messana asked Rome to expel the Carthaginians.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Rome entered this war because Syracuse and Messana were too close to the newly conquered Greek cities of Southern Italy and Carthage was now able to make an offensive through Roman territory; along with this, Rome could extend its domain over Sicily.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Carthage was a maritime power, and the Roman lack of ships and naval experience made the path to the victory a long and difficult one for the Roman Republic.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Despite this, after more than 20 years of war, Rome defeated Carthage and a peace treaty was signed.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Among the reasons for the Second Punic War was the subsequent war reparations Carthage acquiesced to at the end of the First Punic War.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The war began with the audacious invasion of Hispania by Hannibal, who marched through Hispania to the Italian Alps.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Hannibal's invasion lasted over 16 years, ravaging Italy, but ultimately Carthage was defeated in the decisive Battle of Zama in October 202 BC.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] More than a half century after these events, Carthage was left humiliated and the Republic's focus was now directed towards the Hellenistic kingdoms of Greece and revolts in Hispania.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] However, Carthage, having paid the war indemnity, felt that its commitments and submission to Rome had ceased, a vision not shared by the Roman Senate.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The Third Punic War began when Rome declared war against Carthage in 149 BC.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Carthage resisted well at the first strike but could not withstand the attack of Scipio Aemilianus, who entirely destroyed the city, enslaved all the citizens and gained control of that region, which became the province of Africa.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] All these wars resulted in Rome's first overseas conquests (Sicily, Hispania and Africa) and the rise of Rome as a significant imperial power.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] After defeating the Macedonian and Seleucid Empires in the 2nd century BC, the Romans became the dominant people of the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The conquest of the Hellenistic kingdoms brought the Roman and Greek cultures in closer contact and the Roman elite, once rural, became cosmopolitan.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Foreign dominance led to internal strife.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Senators became rich at the provinces' expense; soldiers, who were mostly small-scale farmers, were away from home longer and could not maintain their land; and the increased reliance on foreign slaves and the growth of *latifundia* reduced the availability of paid work.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Income from war booty, mercantilism in the new provinces, and tax farming created new economic opportunities for the wealthy, forming a new class of merchants, called the equestrians.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The **lex Claudia** forbade members of the Senate from engaging in commerce, so while the equestrians could theoretically join the Senate, they were severely restricted in political power.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The Senate squabbled perpetually, repeatedly blocked important land reforms and refused to give the equestrian class a larger say in the government.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Violent gangs of the urban unemployed, controlled by rival Senators, intimidated the electorate through violence.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The situation came to a head in the late 2nd century BC under the Gracchi brothers, a pair of tribunes who attempted to pass land reform legislation that would redistribute the major patrician landholdings among the plebeians.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Both brothers were killed and the Senate passed reforms reversing the Gracchi brother's actions.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] This led to the growing divide of the plebeian groups (*populares*) and equestrian classes (*optimates*).
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Gaius Marius soon became a leader of the Republic, holding the first of his seven consulships (an unprecedented number) in 107 BC by arguing that his former patron Quintus Caecilius Metellus Numidicus was not able to defeat and capture the Numidian king Jugurtha.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Marius then started his military reform: in his recruitment to fight Jugurtha, he levied the very poor (an innovation), and many landless men entered the army.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Marius was elected for five consecutive consulships from 104 to 100 BC, as Rome needed a military leader to defeat the Cimbri and the Teutones, who were threatening Rome.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] After Marius's retirement, Rome had a brief peace, during which the Italian *socii* ('allies') requested Roman citizenship and voting rights.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The reformist Marcus Livius Drusus supported their legal process but was assassinated, and the *socii* revolted against the Romans in the Social War.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] At one point both consuls were killed; Marius was appointed to command the army together with Lucius Julius Caesar and Lucius Cornelius Sulla.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] By the end of the Social War, Marius and Sulla were the premier military men in Rome and their partisans were in conflict, both sides jostling for power.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] In 88 BC, Sulla was elected for his first consulship and his first assignment was to defeat Mithridates VI of Pontus, whose intentions were to conquer the Eastern part of the Roman territories.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] However, Marius's partisans managed his installation to the military command, defying Sulla and the Senate.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] To consolidate his own power, Sulla conducted a surprising and illegal action: he marched to Rome with his legions, killing all those who showed support to Marius's cause.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] In the following year, 87 BC, Marius, who had fled at Sulla's march, returned to Rome while Sulla was campaigning in Greece.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] He seized power along with the consul Lucius Cornelius Cinna and killed the other consul, Gnaeus Octavius, achieving his seventh consulship.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Marius and Cinna revenged their partisans by conducting a massacre.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Marius died in 86 BC, due to age and poor health, just a few months after seizing power.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Cinna exercised absolute power until his death in 84 BC.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] After returning from his Eastern campaigns, Sulla had a free path to reestablish his own power.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] In 83 BC he made his second march on Rome and began a time of terror: thousands of nobles, knights and senators were executed.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Sulla held two dictatorships and one more consulship, which began the crisis and decline of Roman Republic.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] In the mid-1st century BC, Roman politics were restless.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Political divisions in Rome split into one of two groups, *populares* (who hoped for the support of the people) and *optimates* (the 'best', who wanted to maintain exclusive aristocratic control).
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Sulla overthrew all populist leaders and his constitutional reforms removed powers (such as those of the tribune of the plebs) that had supported populist approaches.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Meanwhile, social and economic stresses continued to build; Rome had become a metropolis with a super-rich aristocracy, debt-ridden aspirants, and a large proletariat often of impoverished farmers.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The latter groups supported the Catilinarian conspiracy—a resounding failure since the consul Marcus Tullius Cicero quickly arrested and executed the main leaders.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Julius Caesar reconciled the two most powerful men in Rome: Marcus Licinius Crassus, who had financed much of his earlier career, and Crassus' rival, Gnaeus Pompeius Magnus (anglicised as Pompey), to whom he married his daughter.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] He formed them into a new informal alliance including himself, the First Triumvirate ('three men').
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Caesar's daughter died in childbirth in 54 BC, and in 53 BC, Crassus invaded Parthia and was killed in the Battle of Carrhae; the Triumvirate disintegrated.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Caesar conquered Gaul, obtained immense wealth, respect in Rome and the loyalty of battle-hardened legions.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] He became a threat to Pompey and was loathed by many *optimates*.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Confident that Caesar could be stopped by legal means, Pompey's party tried to strip Caesar of his legions, a prelude to Caesar's trial, impoverishment, and exile.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] To avoid this fate, Caesar crossed the Rubicon River and invaded Rome in 49 BC.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The Battle of Pharsalus was a brilliant victory for Caesar and in this and other campaigns, he destroyed all of the *optimates* leaders: Metellus Scipio, Cato the Younger, and Pompey's son, Gnaeus Pompeius Magnus.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Caesar was now pre-eminent over Rome: in five years he held four consulships, two ordinary dictatorships, and two special dictatorships, one for perpetuity.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] He was murdered in 44 BC, on the Ides of March by the *Liberatores*.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Caesar's assassination caused political and social turmoil in Rome; the city was ruled by his friend and colleague, Mark Antony.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Soon afterward, Octavian, whom Caesar adopted through his will, arrived in Rome.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Octavian (historians regard Octavius as Octavian due to the Roman naming conventions) tried to align himself with the Caesarian faction.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] In 43 BC, along with Antony and Marcus Aemilius Lepidus, Caesar's best friend, he legally established the Second Triumvirate.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Upon its formation, 130–300 senators were executed, and their property was confiscated, due to their supposed support for the *Liberatores*.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] In 42 BC, the Senate deified Caesar as *Divus Iulius*; Octavian thus became *Divi filius*, the son of the deified.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] In the same year, Octavian and Antony defeated both Caesar's assassins and the leaders of the *Liberatores*, Marcus Junius Brutus and Gaius Cassius Longinus, in the Battle of Philippi.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The Second Triumvirate was marked by the proscriptions of many senators and *equites*: after a revolt led by Antony's brother Lucius Antonius, more than 300 senators and *equites* involved were executed, although Lucius was spared.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The Triumvirate divided the Empire among the triumvirs: Lepidus was given charge of Africa, Antony, the eastern provinces, and Octavian remained in Italia and controlled Hispania and Gaul.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The Second Triumvirate expired in 38 BC but was renewed for five more years.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] However, the relationship between Octavian and Antony had deteriorated, and Lepidus was forced to retire in 36 BC after betraying Octavian in Sicily.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] By the end of the Triumvirate, Antony was living in Ptolemaic Egypt, ruled by his lover, Cleopatra VII.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Antony's affair with Cleopatra was seen as an act of treason, since she was queen of another country.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Additionally, Antony adopted a lifestyle considered too extravagant and Hellenistic for a Roman statesman.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Following Antony's Donations of Alexandria, which gave to Cleopatra the title of "Queen of Kings", and to Antony's and Cleopatra's children the regal titles to the newly conquered Eastern territories, war between Octavian and Antony broke out.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Octavian annihilated Egyptian forces in the Battle of Actium in 31 BC.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Now Egypt was conquered by the Roman Empire.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] In 27 BC and at the age of 36, Octavian was the sole Roman leader.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] In that year, he took the name *Augustus*.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] That event is usually taken by historians as the beginning of Roman Empire.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Officially, the government was republican, but Augustus assumed absolute powers.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] His reform of the government brought about a two-century period colloquially referred to by Romans as the Pax Romana.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The Julio-Claudian dynasty was established by Augustus.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The emperors of this dynasty were Augustus, Tiberius, Caligula, Claudius and Nero.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The Julio-Claudians started the destruction of republican values, but on the other hand, they boosted Rome's status as the central power in the Mediterranean region.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] While Caligula and Nero are usually remembered in popular culture as dysfunctional emperors, Augustus and Claudius are remembered as successful in politics and the military.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] This dynasty instituted imperial tradition in Rome and frustrated any attempt to reestablish a Republic.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] 27 BC – AD 14) gathered almost all the republican powers under his official title, *princeps*, and diminished the political influence of the senatorial class by boosting the equestrian class.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The senators lost their right to rule certain provinces, like Egypt, since the governor of that province was directly nominated by the emperor.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The creation of the Praetorian Guard and his reforms in the military, creating a standing army with a fixed size of 28 legions, ensured his total control over the army.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Compared with the Second Triumvirate's epoch, Augustus' reign as *princeps* was very peaceful, which led the people and the nobles of Rome to support Augustus, increasing his strength in political affairs.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] His generals were responsible for the field command, gaining such commanders as Marcus Vipsanius Agrippa, Nero Claudius Drusus and Germanicus much respect from the populace and the legions.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Augustus intended to extend the Roman Empire to the whole known world, and in his reign, Rome conquered Cantabria, Aquitania, Raetia, Dalmatia, Illyricum and Pannonia.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Under Augustus' reign, Roman literature grew steadily in what is known as the Golden Age of Latin Literature.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Poets like Virgil, Horace, Ovid and Rufus developed a rich literature, and were close friends of Augustus.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Along with Maecenas, he sponsored patriotic poems, such as Virgil's epic *Aeneid* and historiographical works like those of Livy.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Augustus continued the changes to the calendar promoted by Caesar, and the month of August is named after him.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Augustus brought a peaceful and thriving era to Rome, known as *Pax Romana*.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The Julio-Claudians continued to rule Rome after Augustus' death in 14 AD and remained in power until the death of Nero in 68 AD.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Influenced by his wife, Livia Drusilla, Augustus appointed her son from another marriage, Tiberius, as his heir.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The Senate agreed with the succession, and granted to Tiberius the same titles and honours once granted to Augustus: the title of *princeps* and *Pater patriae*, and the Civic Crown.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] However, Tiberius was not an enthusiast for political affairs: after agreement with the Senate, he retired to Capri in 26 AD, and left control of the city of Rome in the hands of the praetorian prefect Sejanus (until 31 AD) and Macro (from 31 to 37 AD).
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The male line of the Julio-Claudians was limited to Tiberius' nephew Claudius, his grandson Tiberius Gemellus and his grand-nephew Caligula.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] As Gemellus was still a child, Caligula was chosen to rule the empire.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] He was a popular leader in the first half of his reign, but became a crude and insane tyrant in his years controlling government.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The Praetorian Guard murdered Caligula four years after the death of Tiberius, and, with belated support from the senators, proclaimed his uncle Claudius as the new emperor.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Claudius was not as authoritarian as Tiberius and Caligula.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Claudius conquered Lycia and Thrace; his most important deed was the beginning of the conquest of Britannia.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Claudius was poisoned by his wife, Agrippina the Younger in 54 AD.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] His heir was Nero, son of Agrippina and her former husband, since Claudius' son Britannicus had not reached manhood upon his father's death.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Nero sent his general, Suetonius Paulinus, to invade modern-day Wales, where he encountered stiff resistance.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The Celts there were independent, tough, resistant to tax collectors, and fought Paulinus as he battled his way across from east to west.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] It took him a long time to reach the north-west coast, and in 60 AD he finally crossed the Menai Strait to the sacred island of Mona (Anglesey), the last stronghold of the druids.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] His soldiers attacked the island and massacred the druids: men, women and children, destroyed the shrine and the sacred groves and threw many of the sacred standing stones into the sea.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] While Paulinus and his troops were massacring druids in Mona, the tribes of modern-day East Anglia staged a revolt led by queen Boadicea of the Iceni.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The rebels sacked and burned Camulodunum, Londinium and Verulamium (modern-day Colchester, London and St Albans respectively) before they were crushed by Paulinus.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Boadicea, like Cleopatra before her, committed suicide to avoid the disgrace of being paraded in triumph in Rome.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Nero is widely known as the first persecutor of Christians and for the Great Fire of Rome, rumoured to have been started by the emperor himself.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] A conspiracy against Nero in 65 AD under Calpurnius Piso failed, but in 68 AD the armies under Julius Vindex in Gaul and Servius Sulpicius Galba in modern-day Spain revolted.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Deserted by the Praetorian Guards and condemned to death by the senate, Nero killed himself.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The Flavians were the second dynasty to rule Rome.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] By 68 AD, the year of Nero's death, there was no chance of a return to the Republic, and so a new emperor had to arise.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] After the turmoil in the Year of the Four Emperors, Titus Flavius Vespasianus (anglicised as Vespasian) took control of the empire and established a new dynasty.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Under the Flavians, Rome continued its expansion, and the state remained secure.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The most significant military campaign undertaken during the Flavian period was the siege and destruction of Jerusalem in 70 AD by Titus.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The destruction of the city was the culmination of the Roman campaign in Judea following the Jewish uprising of 66 AD.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The Second Temple was completely demolished, after which Titus' soldiers proclaimed him *imperator* in honour of the victory.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Jerusalem was sacked and much of the population killed or dispersed.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Josephus claims that 1,100,000 people were killed during the siege, of whom a majority were Jewish, and 97,000 were captured and enslaved.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Many fled to areas around the Mediterranean.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Vespasian was a general under Claudius and Nero and fought as a commander in the First Jewish-Roman War.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Following the turmoil of the Year of the Four Emperors, in 69 AD, four emperors were enthroned in turn: Galba, Otho, Vitellius, and, lastly, Vespasian, who crushed Vitellius' forces and became emperor.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] He reconstructed many buildings which were uncompleted, like a statue of Apollo and the temple of *Divus Claudius* ("the deified Claudius"), both initiated by Nero.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Buildings destroyed by the Great Fire of Rome were rebuilt, and he revitalised the Capitol.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Vespasian started the construction of the Flavian Amphitheater, commonly known as the Colosseum.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The historians Josephus and Pliny the Elder wrote their works during Vespasian's reign.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Vespasian was Josephus' sponsor and Pliny dedicated his *Naturalis Historia* to Titus, son of Vespasian.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Vespasian sent legions to defend the eastern frontier in Cappadocia, extended the occupation in Britannia (modern-day England, Wales and southern Scotland) and reformed the tax system.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] He finished the Flavian Amphitheater, using war spoils from the First Jewish-Roman War, and hosted victory games that lasted for a hundred days.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] These games included gladiatorial combats, horse races and a sensational mock naval battle on the flooded grounds of the Colosseum.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Titus died of fever in 81 AD, and was succeeded by his brother Domitian.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] As emperor, Domitian showed the characteristics of a tyrant.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] He ruled for fifteen years, during which time he acquired a reputation for self-promotion as a living god.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] He constructed at least two temples in honour of Jupiter, the supreme deity in Roman religion.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] He was murdered following a plot within his own household.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Following Domitian's murder, the Senate rapidly appointed Nerva as Emperor.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Nerva had noble ancestry, and he had served as an advisor to Nero and the Flavians.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] His rule restored many of the traditional liberties of Rome's upper classes, which Domitian had over-ridden.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The Nerva–Antonine dynasty from 96 AD to 192 AD included the "five good emperors" Nerva, Trajan, Hadrian, Antoninus Pius and Marcus Aurelius.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The Nerva-Antonine dynasty came to an end with Commodus, son of Marcus Aurelius.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Nerva abdicated and died in 98 AD, and was succeeded by the general Trajan.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Trajan is credited with the restoration of traditional privileges and rights of commoner and senatorial classes, which later Roman historians claim to have been eroded during Domitian's autocracy.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Trajan fought three Dacian wars, winning territories roughly equivalent to modern-day Romania and Moldova.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] He undertook an ambitious public building program in Rome, including Trajan's Forum, Trajan's Market and Trajan's Column, with the architect Apollodorus of Damascus.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] He remodelled the Pantheon and extended the Circus Maximus.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] When Parthia appointed a king for Armenia without consulting Rome, Trajan declared war on Parthia and deposed the king of Armenia.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] In 115 he took the Northern Mesopotamian cities of Nisibis and Batnae, organised a province of Mesopotamia (116), and issued coins that claimed Armenia and Mesopotamia were under the authority of the Roman people.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] In that same year, he captured Seleucia and the Parthian capital Ctesiphon (near modern Baghdad).
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] After defeating a Parthian revolt and a Jewish revolt, he withdrew due to health issues, and in 117, he died of edema.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Under Trajan, the Roman Empire had reached the peak of its territorial expansion.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Rome's dominion now spanned 5.0 million square kilometres (1.9 million square miles).
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Trajan's successor Hadrian withdrew all the troops stationed in Parthia, Armenia and Mesopotamia (modern-day Iraq), abandoning Trajan's conquests.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Hadrian's army crushed a revolt in Mauretania and the Bar Kokhba revolt in Judea.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] This was the last large-scale Jewish revolt against the Romans, and was suppressed with massive repercussions in Judea.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Hundreds of thousands of Jews were killed.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Hadrian renamed the province of Judea "Provincia Syria Palaestina", after one of Judea's most hated enemies.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] He constructed fortifications and walls, like the celebrated Hadrian's Wall which separated Roman Britannia and the tribes of modern-day Scotland.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Hadrian promoted culture, especially the Greek.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] He forbade torture and humanised the laws.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] His many building projects included aqueducts, baths, libraries and theatres; additionally, he travelled nearly every province in the Empire to review military and infrastructural conditions.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Following Hadrian's death in 138 AD, his successor Antoninus Pius built temples, theatres, and mausoleums, promoted the arts and sciences, and bestowed honours and financial rewards upon the teachers of rhetoric and philosophy.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] On becoming emperor, Antoninus made few initial changes, leaving intact as far as possible the arrangements instituted by his predecessor.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Antoninus expanded Roman Britannia by invading what is now southern Scotland and building the Antonine Wall.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] He also continued Hadrian's policy of humanising the laws.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] His reign was the most peaceful in the entire history of Roman Empire, he left "an empire in very fine shape.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] It was a height that, arguably, it would never reach again." He died in 161 AD.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Marcus Aurelius, known as the Philosopher, was the last of the Five Good Emperors.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] He was a stoic philosopher and wrote the *Meditations*.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] He defeated barbarian tribes in the Marcomannic Wars as well as the Parthian Empire.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] His co-emperor, Lucius Verus, died in 169 AD, probably from the Antonine Plague, a pandemic that killed nearly five million people through the Empire in 165–180 AD.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] From Nerva to Marcus Aurelius, the empire achieved an unprecedented status.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The powerful influence of laws and manners had gradually cemented the union of the provinces.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] All the citizens enjoyed and abused the advantages of wealth.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The image of a free constitution was preserved with decent reverence.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The Roman senate appeared to possess the sovereign authority, and devolved on the emperors all the executive powers of government.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Gibbon declared the rule of these "Five Good Emperors" the golden era of the Empire.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] During this time, Rome reached its greatest territorial extent.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Commodus, son of Marcus Aurelius, became emperor after his father's death.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] He is not counted as one of the Five Good Emperors, due to his direct kinship with the latter emperor; in addition, he was militarily passive.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Commodus was killed by a conspiracy involving Quintus Aemilius Laetus and his wife Marcia in late 192 AD.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The following year is known as the Year of the Five Emperors, during which Helvius Pertinax, Didius Julianus, Pescennius Niger, Clodius Albinus and Septimius Severus held the imperial dignity.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Pertinax, a member of the senate who had been one of Marcus Aurelius's right-hand men, was the choice of Laetus, and he ruled vigorously and judiciously.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Laetus soon became jealous and instigated Pertinax's murder by the Praetorian Guard, who then auctioned the empire to the highest bidder, Didius Julianus, for 25,000 sesterces per man.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The people of Rome were appalled and appealed to the frontier legions to save them.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The legions of three frontier provinces—Britannia, Pannonia Superior, and Syria—resented being excluded from the "donative" and replied by declaring their individual generals to be emperor.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Lucius Septimius Severus Geta, the Pannonian commander, bribed the opposing forces, pardoned the Praetorian Guards and installed himself as emperor.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] He and his successors governed with the legions' support.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The changes on coinage and military expenditures were the root of the financial crisis that marked the Crisis of the Third Century.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Severus was enthroned after invading Rome and having Didius Julianus killed.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Severus attempted to revive totalitarianism and, addressing the Roman people and Senate, praised the severity and cruelty of Marius and Sulla, which worried the senators.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] When Parthia invaded Roman territory, Severus successfully waged war against that country.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Notwithstanding this military success, Severus failed in invading Hatra, a rich Arabian city.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Severus killed his legate, who was gaining respect from the legions; and his soldiers fell victim to famine.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] After this disastrous campaign, he withdrew.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Severus also intended to vanquish the whole of Britannia.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] To achieve this, he waged war against the Caledonians.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] However, he became ill and died in 211 AD.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] His sons Caracalla and Geta were made emperors.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Caracalla had his brother, a youth, assassinated in his mother's arms, and may have murdered 20,000 of Geta's followers.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] He continued Severus' policy and gained respect from the legions.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Knowing that the citizens of Alexandria disliked him and were denigrating his character, Caracalla served a banquet for its notable citizens, after which his soldiers killed all the guests.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] From the security of the temple of Sarapis, he then directed an indiscriminate slaughter of Alexandria's people.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] In 212, he issued the Edict of Caracalla, giving full Roman citizenship to all free men living in the Empire, with the exception of the *dediticii*, people who had become subject to Rome through surrender in war, and freed slaves.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Mary Beard points to the edict as a fundamental turning point, after which *Rome* was "effectively a new state masquerading under an old name".
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Macrinus conspired to have Caracalla assassinated by one of his soldiers during a pilgrimage to the Temple of the Moon in Carrhae, in 217 AD.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Macrinus assumed power, but soon removed himself from Rome to the east and Antioch.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] His brief reign ended in 218, when the youngster Bassianus, high priest of the temple of the Sun at Emesa, and supposedly illegitimate son of Caracalla, was declared Emperor by the disaffected soldiers of Macrinus.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] He adopted the name of Antoninus but history has named him after his Sun god Elagabalus, represented on Earth in the form of a large black stone.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] An incompetent and lascivious ruler, Elagabalus adopted his cousin Severus Alexander, as Caesar, but subsequently grew jealous and attempted to assassinate him.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] However, the Praetorian guard preferred Alexander, murdered Elagabalus, dragged his mutilated corpse through the streets of Rome, and threw it into the Tiber.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Alexander waged war against many foes, including the revitalised Persia and also the Germanic peoples, who invaded Gaul.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] His losses generated dissatisfaction among his soldiers, and some of them murdered him during his Germanic campaign in 235 AD.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] A disastrous scenario emerged after the death of Alexander Severus: the Roman state was plagued by civil wars, external invasions, political chaos, pandemics and economic depression.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The old Roman values had fallen, and Mithraism and Christianity had begun to spread through the populace.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Emperors were no longer men linked with nobility; they usually were born in lower-classes of distant parts of the Empire.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] These men rose to prominence through military ranks, and became emperors through civil wars.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] There were 26 emperors in a 49-year period, a signal of political instability.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Maximinus Thrax was the first ruler of that time, governing for just three years.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Others ruled just for a few months, like Gordian I, Gordian II, Balbinus and Hostilian.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The population and the frontiers were abandoned, since the emperors were mostly concerned with defeating rivals and establishing their power.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The economy also suffered: massive military expenditures from the Severi caused a devaluation of Roman coins.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Hyperinflation came at this time as well.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The Plague of Cyprian broke out in 250 and killed a huge portion of the population.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] In 260 AD, the provinces of Syria Palaestina, Asia Minor and Egypt separated from the rest of the Roman state to form the Palmyrene Empire, ruled by Queen Zenobia and centered on Palmyra.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] In that same year the Gallic Empire was created by Postumus, retaining Britannia and Gaul.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] These countries separated from Rome after the capture of emperor Valerian by the Sassanids of Persia, the first Roman ruler to be captured by his enemies; it was a humiliating fact for the Romans.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The crisis began to recede during the reigns of Claudius Gothicus (268–270), who defeated the Gothic invaders, and Aurelian (271–275), who reconquered both the Gallic and Palmyrene Empires.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The crisis was overcome during the reign of Diocletian.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] In 284 AD, Diocletian was hailed as Imperator by the eastern army.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Diocletian healed the empire from the crisis, by political and economic shifts.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] A new form of government was established: the Tetrarchy.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The Empire was divided among four emperors, two in the West and two in the East.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The first tetrarchs were Diocletian (in the East), Maximian (in the West), and two junior emperors, Galerius (in the East) and Flavius Constantius (in the West).
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] To adjust the economy, Diocletian made several tax reforms.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Diocletian expelled the Persians who plundered Syria and conquered some barbarian tribes with Maximian.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] He adopted many behaviours of Eastern monarchs.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Anyone in the presence of the emperor had now to prostrate himself—a common act in the East, but never practised in Rome before.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Diocletian did not use a disguised form of Republic, as the other emperors since Augustus had done.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Between 290 and 330, half a dozen new capitals had been established by the members of the Tetrarchy, officially or not: Antioch, Nicomedia, Thessalonike, Sirmium, Milan, and Trier.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Diocletian was also responsible for a significant Christian persecution.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] In 303 he and Galerius started the persecution and ordered the destruction of all the Christian churches and scripts and forbade Christian worship.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Diocletian abdicated in 305 AD together with Maximian, thus, he was the first Roman emperor to resign.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] His reign ended the traditional form of imperial rule, the Principate (from princeps) and started the Tetrarchy.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Constantine assumed the empire as a tetrarch in 306.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] He conducted many wars against the other tetrarchs.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] In 313, he issued the Edict of Milan, which granted liberty for Christians to profess their religion.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Constantine was converted to Christianity, enforcing the Christian faith.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] He began the Christianization of the Empire and of Europe—a process concluded by the Catholic Church in the Middle Ages.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] He was defeated by the Franks and the Alamanni during 306–308.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] In 324 he defeated another tetrarch, Licinius, and controlled all the empire, as it was before Diocletian.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] To celebrate his victories and Christianity's relevance, he rebuilt Byzantium and renamed it Nova Roma ("New Rome"); but the city soon gained the informal name of Constantinople ("City of Constantine").
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The reign of Julian, who under the influence of his adviser Mardonius attempted to restore Classical Roman and Hellenistic religion, only briefly interrupted the succession of Christian emperors.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Constantinople served as a new capital for the Empire.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] In fact, Rome had lost its central importance since the Crisis of the Third Century—Mediolanum was the western capital from 286 to 330, until the reign of Honorius, when Ravenna was made capital, in the 5th century.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Constantine's administrative and monetary reforms, that reunited the Empire under one emperor, and rebuilt the city of Byzantium, as Constantinopolis Nova Roma, changed the high period of the ancient world.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] In the late 4th and 5th centuries the Western Empire entered a critical stage which terminated with the fall of the Western Roman Empire.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The next emperor, Theodosius I (379–395), gave even more force to the Christian faith, and after his death, the Empire was divided into the Eastern Roman Empire, ruled by Arcadius and the Western Roman Empire, commanded by Honorius, both of which were Theodosius' sons.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The situation became more critical in 408, after the death of Stilicho, a general who tried to reunite the Empire and repel barbarian invasion in the early years of the 5th century.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] In 410, the Theodosian dynasty saw the Visigoths sack Rome.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] During the 5th century, the Western Empire experienced a significant reduction of its territory.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The Vandals conquered North Africa, the Visigoths claimed the southern part of Gaul, Gallaecia was taken by the Suebi, Britannia was abandoned by the central government, and the Empire suffered further from the invasions of Attila, chief of the Huns.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] General Orestes refused to meet the demands of the barbarian "allies" who now formed the army, and tried to expel them from Italy.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Unhappy with this, their chieftain Odoacer defeated and killed Orestes, invaded Ravenna and dethroned Romulus Augustus, son of Orestes.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] This event of 476, usually marks the end of Classical antiquity and beginning of the Middle Ages.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The Roman noble and former emperor Julius Nepos continued to rule as emperor from Dalmatia even after the deposition of Romulus Augustus until his death in 480.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Some historians consider him to be the last emperor of the Western Empire instead of Romulus Augustus.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] After 1200 years of independence and nearly 700 years as a great power, the rule of Rome in the West ended.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Various reasons for Rome's fall have been proposed, including loss of Republicanism, moral decay, military tyranny, class war, slavery, economic stagnation, environmental change, disease, the decline of the Roman race, as well as the inevitable ebb and flow that all civilisations experience.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The Eastern Empire survived for almost 1000 years after the fall of its Western counterpart and became the most stable Christian realm during the Middle Ages.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] During the 6th century, Justinian reconquered the Italian peninsula from the Ostrogoths, North Africa from the Vandals, and southern Hispania from the Visigoths.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] But within a few years of Justinian's death, Byzantine possessions in Italy were greatly reduced by the Lombards who settled in the peninsula.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] In the east, partially due to the weakening effect of the Plague of Justinian as well as a series of mutually destructive wars against the Persian Sassanian Empire, the Byzantines were threatened by the rise of Islam.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Its followers rapidly brought about the conquest of the Levant, the conquest of North Africa and the conquest of Egypt during the Arab–Byzantine wars, and soon presented a direct threat to Constantinople.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] In the following century, the Arabs captured southern Italy and Sicily.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] In the west, Slavic populations penetrated deep into the Balkans.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The Byzantine Romans, however, managed to stop further Islamic expansion into their lands during the 8th century and, beginning in the 9th century, reclaimed parts of the conquered lands.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] In 1000 AD, the Eastern Empire was at its height: Basil II reconquered Bulgaria and Armenia, and culture and trade flourished.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] However, soon after, this expansion was abruptly stopped in 1071 with the Byzantine defeat in the Battle of Manzikert.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The aftermath of this battle sent the empire into a protracted period of decline.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] Two decades of internal strife and Turkic invasions ultimately led Emperor Alexios I Komnenos to send a call for help to the Western European kingdoms in 1095.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The West responded with the Crusades, eventually resulting in the Sack of Constantinople by participants of the Fourth Crusade.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The conquest of Constantinople in 1204 fragmented what remained of the Empire into successor states; the ultimate victor was the Empire of Nicaea.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] After the recapture of Constantinople by Imperial forces, the Empire was little more than a Greek state confined to the Aegean coast.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p01] The Eastern Roman (Byzantine) Empire collapsed when Mehmed the Conqueror conquered Constantinople on 29 May 1453.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] The imperial city of Rome was the largest urban center in the empire, with a population variously estimated from 450,000 to close to one million.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Around 20% of the population under jurisdiction of ancient Rome (25–40%, depending on the standards used, in Roman Italy) lived in innumerable urban centers, with population of 10,000 and more and several military settlements, a very high rate of urbanisation by pre-industrial standards.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Most of those centers had a forum, temples, and other buildings similar to Rome's.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] The average life expectancy in the Middle Empire was about 26–28 years.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] The roots of the legal principles and practices of the ancient Romans may be traced to the Law of the Twelve Tables promulgated in 449 BC and to the codification of law issued by order of Emperor Justinian I around 530 AD (see *Corpus Juris Civilis*).
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Roman law as preserved in Justinian's codes continued into the Byzantine Roman Empire, and formed the basis of similar codifications in continental Western Europe.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Roman law continued, in a broader sense, to be applied throughout most of Europe until the end of the 17th century.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] The major divisions of the law of ancient Rome, as contained within the Justinian and Theodosian law codes, consisted of *Jus civile*, *Jus gentium*, and *Jus naturale*.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] The *Jus civile* ('citizen law') was the body of common laws that applied to Roman citizens.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] *Praetor Urbanus*) were the people who had jurisdiction over cases involving citizens.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] The *Jus gentium* ('law of nations') was the body of common laws that applied to foreigners, and their dealings with Roman citizens.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] *Praetor Peregrinus*) were the people who had jurisdiction over cases involving citizens and foreigners.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] *Jus naturale* encompassed natural law, the body of laws that were considered common to all beings.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Roman society is largely viewed as hierarchical, with slaves (*servi*) at the bottom, freedmen (*liberti*) above them, and free-born citizens (*cives*) at the top.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] The broadest, and earliest, division was between the patricians, who could trace their ancestry to one of the 100 patriarchs at the founding of the city, and the plebeians, who could not.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] This became less important in the later Republic, as some plebeian families became wealthy and entered politics, and some patrician families fell economically.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Anyone, patrician or plebeian, who could count a consul as his ancestor was a noble (*nobilis*); a man who was the first of his family to hold the consulship, such as Marius or Cicero, was known as a *novus homo* ('new man') and ennobled his descendants.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Patrician ancestry, however, still conferred considerable prestige, and many religious offices remained restricted to patricians.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] A class division originally based on military service became more important.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Membership of these classes was determined periodically by the censors, according to property.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] The wealthiest were the Senatorial class, who dominated politics and command of the army.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Next came the equestrians (*equites*, sometimes translated "knights"), originally those who could afford a warhorse, and who formed a powerful mercantile class.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Several further classes, originally based on the military equipment their members could afford, followed, with the *proletarii*, citizens who had no property other than their children, at the bottom.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Before the reforms of Marius they were ineligible for military service and are often described as being just above freed slaves in wealth and prestige.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Voting power in the Republic depended on class.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Citizens were enrolled in voting "tribes", but the tribes of the richer classes had fewer members than the poorer ones, all the *proletarii* being enrolled in a single tribe.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Voting was done in class order, from top down, and stopped as soon as most of the tribes had been reached, so the poorer classes were often unable to cast their votes.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Women in ancient Rome shared some basic rights with their male counterparts, but were not fully regarded as citizens and were thus not allowed to vote or take part in politics.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] At the same time the limited rights of women were gradually expanded (due to emancipation) and women reached freedom from *pater familias*, gained property rights and even had more juridical rights than their husbands, but still no voting rights, and were absent from politics.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Allied foreign cities were often given the Latin Rights, an intermediary level between full citizens and foreigners (*peregrini*), which gave their citizens rights under Roman law and allowed their leading magistrates to become full Roman citizens.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] While there were varying degrees of Latin rights, the main division was between those *cum suffragio* ('with vote'; enrolled in a Roman tribe and able to take part in the *comitia tributa*) and *sine suffragio* ('without vote'; could not take part in Roman politics).
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] In the early Republic, there were no public schools, so boys were taught to read and write by their parents, or by educated slaves, called *paedagogi*, usually of Greek origin.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] The primary aim of education during this period was to train young men in agriculture, warfare, Roman traditions, and public affairs.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Young boys learned much about civic life by accompanying their fathers to religious and political functions, including the Senate for the sons of nobles.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] The sons of nobles were apprenticed to a prominent political figure at the age of 16, and campaigned with the army from the age of 17.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Educational practices were modified after the conquest of the Hellenistic kingdoms in the 3rd century BC and the resulting Greek influence, although Roman educational practices were still much different from Greek ones.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Beginning at age 12, students went to secondary schools, where the teacher (now called a *grammaticus*) taught them about Greek and Roman literature.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] At the age of 16, some students went on to rhetoric school (where the teacher, usually Greek, was called a *rhetor*).
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Education at this level prepared students for legal careers, and required that the students memorise the laws of Rome.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Initially, Rome was ruled by kings, who were elected from each of Rome's major tribes in turn.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] The exact nature of the king's power is uncertain.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] He may have held near-absolute power, or may have merely been the chief executive of the Senate and the people.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] In military matters, the king's authority (*Imperium*) was likely absolute.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] He was also the head of the state religion.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] The class struggles of the Roman Republic resulted in an unusual mixture of democracy and oligarchy.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] The word republic comes from the Latin *res publica*, which literally translates to 'public business'.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Roman laws traditionally could only be passed by a vote of the Popular assembly (Comitia Tributa).
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Likewise, candidates for public positions had to run for election by the people.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] However, the Roman Senate represented an oligarchic institution, which acted as an advisory body.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] In the Republic, the Senate held actual authority (*auctoritas*), but no real legislative power; it was technically only an advisory council.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] However, as the Senators were individually very influential, it was difficult to accomplish anything against the collective will of the Senate.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] New senators were chosen from among the most accomplished patricians by censors (*Censura*), who could also remove a senator from his office if he was found "morally corrupt".
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Later, under the reforms of the dictator Sulla, quaestors were made automatic members of the Senate, though most of his reforms did not survive.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] The Republic had no fixed bureaucracy, and collected taxes through the practice of tax farming.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Government positions such as quaestor, aedile, or praefect were funded by the office-holder.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] To prevent any citizen from gaining too much power, new magistrates were elected annually and had to share power with a colleague.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] For example, under normal conditions, the highest authority was held by two consuls.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] In an emergency, a temporary dictator could be appointed.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Throughout the Republic, the administrative system was revised several times to comply with new demands.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] In the end, it proved inefficient for controlling the ever-expanding dominion of Rome, contributing to the establishment of the Roman Empire.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] In the early Empire, the pretense of a republican form of government was maintained.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] The Roman emperor was portrayed as only a *princeps*, or 'first citizen', and the Senate gained legislative power and all legal authority previously held by the popular assemblies.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] However, the rule of the Emperors became increasingly autocratic, and the Senate was reduced to an advisory body appointed by the Emperor.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] The Empire did not inherit a set bureaucracy from the Republic, since the Republic did not have any permanent governmental structures apart from the Senate.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] The Emperor appointed assistants and advisers, but the state lacked many institutions, such as a centrally planned budget.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Some historians have cited this as a significant reason for the decline of the Roman Empire.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] 500 BC) was, like those of other contemporary city-states influenced by Greek civilisation, a citizen *militia* that practised hoplite tactics.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] It was small and organised in five classes (in parallel to the *comitia centuriata*, the body of citizens organised politically), with three providing hoplites and two providing light infantry.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] The early Roman army was tactically limited and its stance during this period was essentially defensive.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] By the 3rd century BC, the Romans abandoned the hoplite formation in favour of a more flexible system in which smaller groups of 120 (or sometimes 60) men called '*maniples* could manoeuvre more independently on the battlefield.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Thirty maniples arranged in three lines with supporting troops constituted a legion, totalling between 4,000 and 5,000 men.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] The early Republican legion consisted of five sections: manipular heavy infantry (*hastati*, *principes* and *triarii*), a force of light infantry (*velites*), and the cavalry (*equites*).
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] With the new organisation came a new orientation toward the offensive and a much more aggressive posture toward adjoining city-states.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Until the late Republican period, the typical legionary was a property-owning citizen farmer from a rural area (an *adsiduus*) who served for particular (often annual) campaigns, and who supplied his own equipment.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] After 200 BC, economic conditions in rural areas deteriorated as manpower needs increased, so that the property qualifications for compulsory service were gradually reduced.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Beginning in the 3rd century BC, legionaries were paid a stipend.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] By the time of Augustus, the ideal of the citizen-soldier had been abandoned and the legions had become fully professional.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] At the end of the Civil War, Augustus reorganised Roman military forces, discharging soldiers and disbanding legions.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] He retained 28 legions, distributed through the provinces of the Empire.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] During the Principate, the tactical organisation of the Army continued to evolve.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] The *auxilia* remained independent cohorts, and legionary troops often operated as groups of cohorts rather than as full legions.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] A new and versatile type of unit, the *cohortes equitatae*, combined cavalry and legionaries in a single formation.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] They could be stationed at garrisons or outposts and could fight on their own as balanced small forces or combine with similar units as a larger, legion-sized force.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] This increase in organizational flexibility helped ensure the long-term success of Roman military forces.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] The Emperor Gallienus (253–268 AD) began a reorganisation that created the last military structure of the late Empire.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Withdrawing some legionaries from the fixed bases on the border, Gallienus created mobile forces (the *comitatenses*, or field armies) and stationed them behind and at some distance from the borders as a strategic reserve.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] The border troops (*limitanei*) stationed at fixed bases continued to be the first line of defence.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] The basic units of the field army were regimental; *legiones* or *auxilia* for infantry and *vexillationes* for cavalry.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Nominal strengths may have been 1,200 men for infantry regiments and 600 for cavalry, but actual troop levels could have been much lower—800 infantry and 400 cavalry.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Many infantry and cavalry regiments operated in pairs under the command of a *comes*.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Field armies included regiments recruited from allied tribes and known as *foederati*.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] By 400 AD, *foederati* regiments had become permanently established units of the Roman army, paid and equipped by the Empire, led by a Roman tribune and used just as Roman units were used.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] The Empire also used groups of barbarians to fight along with the legions as allies without integration into the field armies, under overall command of a Roman general, but led by their own officers.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Military leadership evolved over the course of the history of Rome.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Under the monarchy, the hoplite armies were led by the kings.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] During the early and middle Roman Republic, military forces were under the command of one of the two elected consuls for the year.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] During the later Republic, members of the Roman Senatorial elite, as part of the normal sequence of elected public offices known as the *cursus honorum*, would have served first as *quaestor* (often posted as deputies to field commanders), then as *praetor*.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Following the end of a term as praetor or consul, a Senator might be appointed by the Senate as a *propraetor* or *proconsul* (depending on the highest office held before) to govern a foreign province.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Under Augustus, whose most important political priority was to place the military under a permanent and unitary command, the Emperor was the legal commander of each legion but exercised that command through a *legatus* (legate) he appointed from the Senatorial elite.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] During the later stages of the Imperial period (beginning perhaps with Diocletian), the Augustan model was abandoned.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Provincial governors were stripped of military authority, and command of the armies in a group of provinces was given to generals (*duces*) appointed by the Emperor.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] These were no longer members of the Roman elite but men who came up through the ranks and had seen much practical soldiering.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] With increasing frequency, these men attempted (sometimes successfully) to usurp the positions of the Emperors.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Decreased resources, increasing political chaos and civil war eventually left the Western Empire vulnerable to attack and takeover by neighbouring barbarian peoples.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Less is known about the Roman navy than the Roman army.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Prior to the middle of the 3rd century BC, officials known as *duumviri navales* commanded a fleet of twenty ships used mainly to control piracy.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] This fleet was given up in 278 AD and replaced by allied forces.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] The First Punic War required that Rome build large fleets, and it did so largely with the assistance of and financing from allies.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] This reliance on allies continued to the end of the Roman Republic.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] The quinquereme was the main warship on both sides of the Punic Wars and remained the mainstay of Roman naval forces until replaced by the time of Caesar Augustus by lighter and more manoeuvrable vessels.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Ships were commanded by a *navarch*, a rank equal to a centurion, who was usually not a citizen.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Potter suggests that because the fleet was dominated by non-Romans, the navy was considered non-Roman and allowed to atrophy in times of peace.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Information suggests that by the time of the late Empire (350 AD), the Roman navy comprised several fleets including warships and merchant vessels for transportation and supply.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Warships were oared sailing galleys with three to five banks of oarsmen.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Fleet bases included such ports as Ravenna, Arles, Aquilea, Misenum and the mouth of the Somme River in the West and Alexandria and Rhodes in the East.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Flotillas of small river craft (*classes*) were part of the *limitanei* (border troops) during this period, based at fortified river harbours along the Rhine and the Danube.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] That prominent generals commanded both armies and fleets suggests that naval forces were treated as auxiliaries to the army and not as an independent service.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] The details of command structure and fleet strengths during this period are not well known, although fleets were commanded by prefects.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Ancient Rome commanded a vast area of land, with tremendous natural and human resources.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] As such, Rome's economy remained focused on farming and trade.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Agricultural free trade changed the Italian landscape, and by the 1st century BC, vast grape and olive estates had supplanted the yeoman farmers, who were unable to match the imported grain price.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] The annexation of Egypt, Sicily and Tunisia in North Africa provided a continuous supply of grains.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] In turn, olive oil and wine were Italy's main exports.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Two-tier crop rotation was practised, but farm productivity was low.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Industrial and manufacturing activities were small.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] The largest such activities were the mining and quarrying of stones, which provided basic construction materials for the buildings of that period.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] In manufacturing, production was on a relatively small scale, and generally consisted of workshops and small factories that employed at most dozens of workers.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] However, some brick factories employed hundreds of workers.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] The economy of the early Republic was largely based on smallholding and paid labour.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] However, foreign wars and conquests made slaves increasingly cheap and plentiful, and by the late Republic, the economy was largely dependent on slave labour for both skilled and unskilled work.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Slaves are estimated to have constituted around 20% of the Roman Empire's population at this time and 40% in the city of Rome.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Only in the Roman Empire, when the conquests stopped and the prices of slaves increased, did hired labour become more economical than slave ownership.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Although barter was used in ancient Rome, and often used in tax collection, Rome had a very developed coinage system, with brass, bronze, and precious metal coins in circulation throughout the Empire and beyond—some have even been discovered in India.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Before the 3rd century BC, copper was traded by weight, measured in unmarked lumps, across central Italy.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] The original copper coins (*as*) had a face value of one Roman pound of copper, but weighed less.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Thus, Roman money's utility as a unit of exchange consistently exceeded its intrinsic value as metal.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] After Nero began debasing the silver denarius, its legal value was an estimated one-third greater than its intrinsic value.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Horses were expensive and other pack animals were slower.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Mass trade on the Roman roads connected military posts, where Roman markets were centered.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] As a result, there was transport of commodities between Roman regions, but increased with the rise of Roman maritime trade in the 2nd century BC.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] During that period, a trading vessel took less than a month to complete a trip from Gades to Alexandria via Ostia, spanning the entire length of the Mediterranean.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Transport by sea was around 60 times cheaper than by land, so the volume for such trips was much larger.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Some economists consider the Roman Empire a market economy, similar in its degree of capitalistic practices to the 17th-century Netherlands and 18th-century England.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] The basic units of Roman society were households and families.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Groups of households connected through the male line formed a family (*gens*), based on blood ties, a common ancestry or adoption.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] During the Republic, some powerful families, or *Gentes Maiores*, came to dominate political life.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Families were headed by their oldest male citizen, the *pater familias* (father of the family), who held lawful authority (*patria potestas*, 'father's power') over wives, sons, daughters, and slaves of the household, and the family's wealth.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] The extreme expressions of this power—the selling or killing of family members for moral or civil offences, including simple disobedience—were very rarely exercised, and were forbidden in the Imperial era.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] A *pater familias* had moral and legal duties towards all family members.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Even the most despotic *pater familias* was expected to consult senior members of his household and *gens* over matters that affected the family's well-being and reputation.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Traditionally, such matters were regarded as outside the purview of the state and its magistrates; under the emperors, they were increasingly subject to state interference and legislation.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Once accepted into their birth family by their fathers, children were potential heirs.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] They could not be lawfully given away, or sold into slavery.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] If parents were unable to care for their child, or if its paternity was in doubt, they could resort to infant exposure (Boswell translates this as being "offered" up to care by the gods or strangers).
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] If a deformed or sickly newborn was patently "unfit to live", killing it was a duty of the *pater familias*.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] A citizen father who exposed a healthy freeborn child was not punished, but automatically lost his *potestas* over that child.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Abandoned children were sometimes adopted; some would have been sold into slavery.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Slavery was near-ubiquitous and almost universally accepted.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] In the early Republic, citizens in debt were allowed to sell their labour, and perhaps their sons, to their debtor in a limited form of slavery called *nexum* but this was abolished in the middle Republic.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Freedom was considered a natural and proper state for citizens; slaves could be lawfully freed, with consent and support of their owners, and still serve their owners' family and financial interests, as freedmen or freed women.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] This was the basis of the client-patron relationship, one of the most important features of Rome's economy and society.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] In law, a *pater familias* held *potestas* over his adult sons with their own households.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] This could give rise to legal anomalies, such as adult sons also having the status of minors.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] No man could be considered a *pater familias*, nor could he truly hold property under law, while his own father lived.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] During Rome's early history, married daughters came under the control (*manus*) of their husbands' *pater familias*.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] By the late Republic, most married women retained lawful connection to their birth family, though any children from the marriage belonged to her husband's family.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] The mother or an elderly relative often raised both boys and girls.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Roman moralists held that marriage and child-raising fulfilled a basic duty to family, *gens*, and the state.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Fathers usually began seeking husbands for their daughters when these reached an age between twelve and fourteen, but most commoner-class women stayed single until their twenties, and in general seem to have been far more independent than wives of the elite.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Divorce required the consent of one party, along with the return of any dowry.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Both parents had power over their children during their minority and adulthood, but husbands had much less control over their wives.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Roman citizen women held a restricted form of citizenship; they could not vote but were protected by law.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] They ran families, could own and run businesses, own and cultivate land, write their own wills, and plead in court on their own behalf, or on behalf of others, all under dispensation of the courts and the nominal supervision of a senior male relative.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] The latter was much resented, and the former had seemingly negligible results.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Aristocratic women seem to have been increasingly disinclined to childbearing.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Roman hours were counted ordinally from dawn to dawn.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Thus, if sunrise was at 6 am, then 6 to 7 am was called the 'first hour'.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Midday was called *meridies*, and it is from this word that the terms *am* (*ante meridiem*) and *pm* (*post meridiem*) stem.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] The English word "noon" comes from *nona* ('ninth (hour)'), which referred to 3 pm in ancient Rome.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] The Romans had clocks (*horologia*), which included giant public sundials (*solaria*) and water clocks (*clepsydrae*).
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] The ancient Roman week originally had eight days, which were identified by letters A to H, with the eighth day being the *nundinum*, or market day, a kind of weekend when farmers sold their produce on the streets.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] The seven-day week, introduced from the East during the early Empire, was officially adopted during the reign of Constantine.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Romans named week days after celestial bodies from at least the 1st century AD.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] The Roman year originally had ten months from Martius (March) to December, with the winter period not included in the calendar.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] The first four months were named after gods (Martius, Aprilis, Maius, Junius) and the others were numbered (Quintilis, Sextilis, September, October, November, and December).
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Numa Pompilius, the second king of Rome (716–673 BC), is said to have introduced the months of January and February, both also named after gods, beginning the 12-month calendar still in use today.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] In 44 BC, the month Quintilis was renamed to Julius (July) after Julius Caesar and in 8 BC, Sextilis was renamed to Augustus (August) after Augustus.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] The Romans had several ways of tracking years.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] One widespread way was the consular dating, which identified years by the two consuls who ruled each year.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Another way, introduced in the late 3rd century AD, was counting years from the *indictio*, a 15-year period based on the announcement of the delivery of food and other goods to the government.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Another way, less popular but more similar to present day, was *ab urbe condita*, which counted years from the mythical foundation of Rome in 753 BC.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Life in ancient Rome revolved around the city of Rome, located on seven hills.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] The city had a vast number of monumental structures like the Colosseum, the Trajan's Forum and the Pantheon.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] It had theatres, gymnasiums, marketplaces, functional sewers, bath complexes complete with libraries and shops, and fountains with fresh drinking water supplied by hundreds of miles of aqueducts.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Throughout the territory under the control of ancient Rome, residential architecture ranged from modest houses to country villas.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] In Rome, there were imperial residences on Palatine Hill.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] The low plebeian and middle equestrian classes lived in the city center, packed into apartments, or insulae, which were almost like modern ghettos.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] These areas, often built by upper class property owners to rent, were often centred upon collegia or taberna.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] These people, provided with a free supply of grain, and entertained by gladiatorial games, were enrolled as clients of patrons among the upper class patricians, whose assistance they sought and whose interests they upheld.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] The native language of the Romans was Latin, an Italic language the grammar of which relies little on word order, conveying meaning through a system of affixes attached to word stems.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Its alphabet was based on the Etruscan alphabet, which was in turn based on the Greek alphabet.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Speakers of Latin could understand both until the 7th century when spoken Latin began to diverge so much that 'Classical' or 'Good Latin' had to be learned as a second language.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] While Latin remained the main written language of the Roman Empire, Greek came to be the language spoken by the well-educated elite, as most of the literature studied by Romans was written in Greek.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Most of the emperors were bilingual but had a preference for Latin in the public sphere for political reasons, a practice that first started during the Punic wars.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] In the eastern part of the Roman Empire (and later the Eastern Roman Empire), Latin was never able to replace Greek, a legacy of the Hellenistic period.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Justinian would be the last emperor to use Latin in government and marks when Greek officially took over.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] The expansion of the Roman Empire spread Latin throughout Europe, and Vulgar Latin evolved into many distinct Romance languages.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Archaic Roman religion, at least concerning the gods, was made up not of written narratives, but rather of complex interrelations between gods and humans.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Unlike in Greek mythology, the gods were not personified, but were vaguely defined sacred spirits called *numina*.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Romans also believed that every person, place or thing had its own *genius*, or divine soul.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] During the Roman Republic, Roman religion was organised under a strict system of priestly offices, which were held by men of senatorial rank.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] The College of Pontifices was uppermost body in this hierarchy, and its chief priest, the *Pontifex Maximus*, was the head of the state religion.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Flamens took care of the cults of various gods, while augurs were trusted with taking the auspices.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] The sacred king took on the religious responsibilities of the deposed kings.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] In the Roman Empire, deceased emperors who had ruled well were deified by their successors and the Senate. and the formalised imperial cult became increasingly prominent.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] As contact with the Greeks increased, the old Roman gods became increasingly associated with Greek gods.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Under the Empire, the Romans absorbed the mythologies of their conquered subjects, often leading to situations in which the temples and priests of traditional Italian deities existed side by side with those of foreign gods.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Beginning with Emperor Nero in the 1st century AD, Roman official policy towards Christianity was negative, and at some point, being a Christian could be punishable by death.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Under Emperor Diocletian, the persecution of Christians reached its peak.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] However, it became an officially supported religion in the Roman state under Diocletian's successor, Constantine I, with the signing of the Edict of Milan in 313, and quickly became dominant.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] All religions except Christianity were prohibited in 391 AD by an edict of Emperor Theodosius I.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Like many ancient cultures, concepts of ethics and morality, while sharing some commonalities with modern society, differed greatly in several important ways.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Because ancient civilisations like Rome were under constant threat of attack from marauding tribes, their culture was necessarily militaristic with martial skills being a prized attribute.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Whereas modern societies consider compassion a virtue, Roman society considered compassion a vice, a moral defect.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] One of the primary purposes of the gladiatorial games was to inoculate Roman citizens from this weakness.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Romans instead prized virtues such as courage and conviction (*virtus*), a sense of duty to one's people, moderation and avoiding excess (*moderatio*), forgiveness and understanding (*clementia*), fairness (*severitas*), and loyalty (*pietas*).
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Roman society had well-established and restrictive norms related to sexuality, though as with many societies, the lion's share of the responsibilities fell on women.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Women were generally expected to be monogamous having only a single husband during their life (*univira*), though this was much less regarded by the elite, especially under the empire.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Women were expected to be modest in public avoiding any provocative appearance and to demonstrate absolute fidelity to their husbands (*pudicitia*).
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Wearing a veil was a common expectation to preserve modesty.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Sex outside of marriage was generally frowned upon for men and women and was made illegal during the imperial period.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Nevertheless, prostitution was an accepted and regulated practice.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Public demonstrations of death, violence, and brutality were used as a source of entertainment in Roman communities; however it was also a way to maintain social order, demonstrate power, and signify communal unity.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Roman painting styles show Greek influences, and surviving examples are primarily frescoes used to adorn the walls and ceilings of country villas, though Roman literature includes mentions of paintings on wood, ivory, and other materials.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Several examples of Roman painting have been found at Pompeii, and from these art historians divide the history of Roman painting into four periods.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] The first style of Roman painting was practised from the early 2nd century BC to the early- or mid-1st century BC.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] It was mainly composed of imitations of marble and masonry, though sometimes including depictions of mythological characters.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] The second style began during the early 1st century BC and attempted to depict realistically three-dimensional architectural features and landscapes.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] The third style occurred during the reign of Augustus (27 BC – 14 AD), and rejected the realism of the second style in favour of simple ornamentation.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] A small architectural scene, landscape, or abstract design was placed in the center with a monochrome background.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] The fourth style, which began in the 1st century AD, depicted scenes from mythology, while retaining architectural details and abstract patterns.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Portrait sculpture used youthful and classical proportions, evolving later into a mixture of realism and idealism.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] During the Antonine and Severan periods, ornate hair and bearding, with deep cutting and drilling, became popular.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Advancements were also made in relief sculptures, usually depicting Roman victories.
[src:antikythera-wreck/ancient-rome-p02] Roman music was largely based on Greek music, and played an important part in many aspects of Roman life.
